<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: MPs seek facts on Lamont donation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WATCHDOGS on MPs' financial dealings have stopped short of launching an
inquiry into Mr Norman Lamont's alleged failure to report an Pounds 18,000
donation from Conservative party sources to help pay his legal bills for
evicting a tenant, Ivo Dawnay writes.
Instead, the Commons' committee on members' interests yesterday asked three
Labour backbench complainants to give more details of the alleged breach of
rules. It offered the chancellor an opportunity to tell his side of the
story.
The committee is scheduled to meet again next week to examine the question
further.
The complaint from Ms Alice Mahon, Mr Alan Milburn and Mr Geoffrey Hoon
argued that Mr Lamont should have registered the payment to comply with
strict rules governing MPs' financial dealings.
The committee must first decide whether the donation was a private gift or
whether it could be deemed to relate to the chancellor's performance of his
duties as a member of the House.
</TEXT>
