<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Plea to EC on fishing curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN last night called on the European Commission to withdraw fish
conservation proposals that would require some British trawlers to be
confined to port for at least 10 consecutive days each calendar month.
Sir Hector Monro, junior Scottish office minister, told the Commons that if
the Commission failed to respond British ministers would 'vigorously' oppose
the proposals when the EC fisheries council meets for talks in Brussels next
week.
While acknowledging that British fishermen felt they had had a 'very rough
ride this year' through enforcement of conservation quotas, he insisted that
some restrictions would continue to be necessary.
Sir Hector explained that the government was trying to find a 'halfway
house' which would avoid British trawlers being tied up in port on
consecutive days.
The government had agreed a programme for the next four years which would
reduce fishing right across the UK fleet through a combination of
decommissioning and licensing measures. 'In this context a 10-day tie-up
targeted at a particular group of boats is unnecessary and inappropriate,'
he said.
Sir Hector confirmed that provisions in the Sea Fish (Conservation) Bill
would enable the government to control the number of days which fishing
vessels spent at sea next year.
Mr Gavin Strang, chief Labour spokesman in the debate, said the government's
failure to introduce a properly managed and socially acceptable
de-commissioning scheme had made a substantial contribution to the 'crisis'
in the industry.
A scheme was needed that provided compensation for all engaged in the
industry and not just for the owners of fishing vessels.
Challenged by Mr David Curry, fisheries minister, about the cost of such a
scheme, Mr Strang retorted that Labour was not advocating that it should be
'on the cheap - far from it'.
Mr Curry said Pounds 25m spread over three years was 'on the table' for a
de-commissioning scheme, 75 per cent provided by the British taxpayer.
He emphasised that a de-commissioning scheme and a system to limit fishing
through 'effort control' would have to go together.
The government secured a majority of 81 (294-213) to defeat a Labour attack
on its conduct of fisheries policy.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
