<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: MoD takes blame for misspent funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE USE of public money to pay for extravagant parties, go-karts and theatre
tickets was an 'institutional failure', Sir Christopher France, permanent
under secretary to the Ministry of Defence, told MPs yesterday.
The Commons public accounts committee called Sir Christopher to explain why
Pounds 1.2m, intended to reward MoD personnel for the success of a
cost-cutting programme which saved Pounds 2.3bn over three years, was
misspent, causing the National Audit Office to qualify the MoD accounts for
1990-91. The Pounds 1.2m formed 13 per cent of the budget allocated to the
incentive and reward scheme.
Parties on the HMS Argus and HMS Galahad to celebrate the 25th anniversary
of the Royal Naval Supply and Transport Service accounted for Pounds
129,000. Other unauthorised expenditure included 56 coaches and minibuses in
Germany, golf club memberships, a caravan and fish tanks.
'I think the failure stretched from headquarters right through the system,'
Sir Christopher said.
He said the amount of money involved was not large, but said: 'It is not
small change - it is like the housemaid's baby, it should not be there at
all.'
He blamed ambiguities in the scheme's guidelines for some of the problems.
According to the guidelines, the fund was to reward 'the whole defence
community', meaning that civilians as well as service personnel should
benefit.
</TEXT>
