<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Thatcher backs Patten over China
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BARONESS THATCHER, the former prime minister, last night used a Lords debate
on Hong Kong and China to make a spirited defence of Mr Chris Patten, the
colony's governor.
Other speakers - including two former governors - expressed regret and alarm
at the possible consequences of the row between Britain and China but Lady
Thatcher praised her former cabinet colleague for his 'great sensitivity and
skill'.
She described the controversial October speech in which Mr Patten outlined
proposals to extend the scope of democracy in Hong Kong as splendid and
magnificently constructed. The governor had not proposed anything that
conflicted with the 1984 Sino-British joint declaration.
In common with other speakers, Lady Thatcher emphasised that Mr Patten's
proposals were 'only a basis for discussion' and expressed 'great
disappointment' that China had so far declined to make its contribution to
the debate.
But while sincerely wishing it will prove possible to 'proceed along with'
China, 'this cannot be at the expense of what we believe to be right,' she
warned. 'In the last resort, it is Britain that has responsibility for
governing Hong Kong up to 1997.'
Lady Thatcher also used the occasion to broadcast a message to the incoming
Clinton administration in the United States that it would be 'profoundly
misguided' to put pressure on China over human rights by restricting trade.
President George Bush had been 'excellently right' to resist using that
blunt weapon, she said.
In his maiden speech in the Lords, Lord Wilson of Tillyorn, Mr Patten's
predecessor as governor, commended the way his successor had endeared
himself to the people of Hong Kong but expressed alarm at the intensity and
implications of the dispute.
He hoped other proposals would indeed be put forward 'so there may be a
chance to find a structure for the 1995 elections which will be satisfactory
to the people of Hong Kong'.
The continuity which had been one of the chief aims and achievements of the
joint declaration was a very important objective for Hong Kong.
Lord Maclehose of Beoch, another former governor, said the violence with
which the Chinese had responded to the proposals had produced what was
approaching a crisis with progress apparently blocked.
He said the Chinese appeared to have a point that the spirit if not the
letter of the 1990 agreement has been breached. If passed into law, Mr
Patten's proposals would operate only from 1995 until 1997. Mr Patten 'may
have been misdirected over these proposals, but I am sure he has the
political experience, flexibility and indeed charisma to lead Hong Kong back
into a working political relationship with China.'
Baroness Dunn, a senior member of Hong Kong's executive council, said
Britain bore a share of the blame for the current predicament. Was it really
surprising, after a history of deals 'cut behind closed doors' that the
Chinese government should find the new British openness of approach
difficult to comprehend, she asked.
Baroness Chalker, foreign office minister, accused China of 'increasingly
strident propaganda attacks.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
