<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Taxpayers 'lost out' in sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TAXPAYERS and consumers lost out to investors in the privatisation of the
electricity industry in 1990, the all-party Commons public accounts
committee said yesterday.
Its report said the Pounds 16.7bn assets owned by the 12 regional
electricity companies were sold for proceeds of Pounds 7.7bn. That sum
consisted of Pounds 4.9bn paid by investors for shares with the remaining
Pounds 2.8bn in the form of debt repayable to the government.
The committee said the cost of servicing that debt was essentially borne by
the electricity consumer through higher electricity bills.
The committee attacked the sharp rise in profits reported by electricity
companies since privatisation, and the strong growth in dividends.
It commented that it would 'not have been unreasonable' for the taxpayer to
share in the growth in profits. Manweb results, Page 24
</TEXT>
