<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Recovery day fails to strike a blow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY's National Day of Recovery, organised by the Trades Union Congress
to link the campaign against pit closures to job losses in general, will be
remembered for a long time at George Fischer Castings in Bedford.
On the day when union representatives around Britain were supposed to be
asking their employers to think of alternatives to redundancy, Fischer told
300 of its 350 workers that their jobs were being transferred to Germany and
Austria.
Mr Mike Pennington, managing director of the Swiss-owned malleable-fittings
maker, said he had not heard of the National Day of Recovery and admitted
that the job losses had 'come as a shock' to most of the workers and their
union.
Since the slump in industrial and commercial construction in the UK, Fischer
has been exporting most of its UK output. But as the German market weakens
as well, customers can be better served from Continental plants.
Overall, the Day of Recovery saw little union activity on jobs. Most big
employers, such as ICI and Unilever, said they had had no formal approach
from unions at national or plant level. There was a demonstration in
Manchester, and a service for recovery at Southwark Cathedral in London
attended by 350 people.
At the TUC's own day-long conference in London the limelight was stolen by
Mr Arthur Scargill, the National Union of Mineworkers president. He reverted
to the militant rhetoric that has been notably absent in recent weeks when
he called for 'a day of action with millions taking part' if the government
did not keep open all 31 pits under review.
His comments were immediately criticised by Mr Bill Jordan, president of the
AEEU craft union, who said they were a throwback to formulas that have never
worked.
The European dimension did at least come to the TUC's rescue. Mr Norman
Willis, TUC general secretary and president of the European Trade Union
Confederation, led a joint European union and employers' delegation to urge
a growth strategy on Mr John Major, the prime minister, for the Edinburgh
summit.
The European unions and employers claim some credit for putting the idea on
the agenda at Edinburgh, and Mr Major said a European Commission plan for
infrastructure investment would be married to UK ideas for improving labour
market flexibility.
