<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Companies face tougher rules on defining shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES will be required to comply with much tougher definitions of
capital instruments in their accounts under a draft financial reporting
standard issued yesterday.
The third financial reporting exposure draft (Fred 3) issued by the
Accounting Standards Board demands more consistent treatment, adequate
disclosure and a true reflection of the costs of capital instruments such as
shares, debentures and loans.
The draft is likely to become a mandatory standard by late next year. Among
the most radical proposals is that convertible debt should be separately
disclosed and included in liabilities until it is actually converted into
equity.
Mr David Tweedie, board chairman, said: 'The main problem with capital
instruments was the diversity of treatment.
'Neither the profit-and-loss account nor balance sheet were comparable. This
will make them comparable.'
Capital instruments will be classified as liabilities if they contain an
obligation to transfer cash or other resources. Liabilities will be split
between convertible and non-convertible instruments.
Shareholders' funds will appear in accounts divided between equity and
non-equity interests. Non-equity will include any shares that have a
restricted right to dividends or are redeemable.
Minority interests will appear between equity interests in subsidiaries and
non-equity interests in subsidiaries. The finance costs of liabilities -
such as interest costs, dividends or premiums payable on redemption - should
be allocated to accounting periods to achieve a constant rate on the amount
outstanding.
The board said the discussion draft on capital instruments issued a year ago
was favourably received. Changes as a result of comments include a
redefinition of short and long-term debt. Short-term borrowings will be
permitted to be reported as long-term if they are under a long-term
financing facility. Short-term commercial paper cannot be reported as
long-term.
Fred 3. Accountancy Books, PO Box 620, Central Milton Keynes. MK9 2JX.
Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
