<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Account standards extended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES WILL be required to apply new accounting standards to all
significant transactions regardless of when they took place, the Accounting
Standards Board ruled yesterday.
In a wide-ranging statement with important implications for covenants and
other legal documents, the board stressed that any transactions that took
place before a standard was introduced must comply with the new standard.
Companies have claimed that adjustments to new standards could mean they
breach contracts and agreements that specify limits on items such as net
worth or gearing.
But the board - with support from the British Banking Association - said
this should be considered when contracts are drawn up, and renegotiated if
necessary after new standards are introduced.
Contracts will use the standards at the time of signing - so-called 'frozen
GAAP' or generally accepted accounting principles.
Mr David Tweedie, board chairman, said: 'This brings everyone on to a
comparable basis. You must make sure covenants deal with accounting
standards at the time of signing. We want to show it as it is.'
The board argued that the exemption of certain transactions meant they were
accounted for in different ways in the same set of accounts, and hindered
comparisons.
</TEXT>
