<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Targets set for Post Office 'unreasonable'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is imposing 'unreasonable and uncommercial' financial targets
on the Post Office, the Post Office Users' National Council, the official
postal services watchdog, said yesterday.
Over the next two financial years the Post Office's contribution to the
government will rise by more than Pounds 200m.
The amount the Post Office has to generate from cashflow above its own
investment needs - negative external financing limits (EFLs) - will increase
from Pounds 68m in 1993-94 and Pounds 70m in 1994-95 to Pounds 180m in both
years.
In a letter to Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, Mr Tom
Corrigan, chairman of the council, said he was 'appalled to find that
without prior mention or justification future Post Office negative external
financing limits have been increased by over 250 per cent'.
Given the recent Post Office pay settlement at twice the 1.5 per cent public
sector rate announced by the government, Mr Corrigan fears the Post Office
will have to find the extra cash by reducing services and investment and
increasing prices. Wages and salaries account for about four fifths of the
Post Office's costs.
The watchdog predicts that there will be 'little or no improvement in postal
quality', warning of significant increases in stamp prices in order to meet
the 'tax on the post'. Mr Corrigan said: 'The arbitrary nature of the
negative EFL target appears unreasonable and uncommercial'.
Earlier in the year the group issued a report on Post Office financial
targets. 'We hoped this would act as a catalyst for debate but regrettably
so far has elicited no response from the government,' Mr Corrigan said.
The Post Office described the targets as 'challenging', but said its record
showed it could meet government targets.
The Department of Trade and Industry said that since there was pressure on
the public sector borrowing requirement 'it is reasonable that the
government should look for a higher rate of return from the Post Office'.
Return to sender, Page 18
