FT  10 DEC 92 / Ford defends car price rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Ian McAllister, chairman of Ford of Britain, yesterday rounded on critics
of the company's latest increases in car prices and claimed that many of the
comments were 'ill-judged'.
Earlier this week Ford announced average price rises from January 4 for its
Fiesta and Escort/Orion cars of 4.5 per cent and for its Sierra and Granada
cars of 7.5 per cent.
Mr McAllister claimed that retail prices of the Fiesta small car range,
excluding car tax, would be only 1.4 per cent to 2.6 per cent higher in
January than at the beginning of this year. Ford had lowered list prices for
the Fiesta twice this year as part of 'aggressive action to stimulate
sales'.
The price of the 1.4 litre Escort CAT LX after the increase would be 7.6 per
cent higher than in January this year. During the year it had significantly
improved the Escort range with the addition of new engines, catalytic
converters as standard equipment and improved safety features.
Mr McAllister claimed that no manufacturer could ignore the impact of the
devaluation of the pound by around 16 per cent and inflation of 4 per cent,
but said that Ford had 'increased prices over the past year by far less'.
However, the Escort/Orion and Fiesta ranges are built in the UK and are
largely shielded from the impact of devaluation. The prices of the
German-built Granada and the Belgian-built Sierra will have risen by around
13 per cent in the 12 months to January.
Mr McAllister said that it was 'absurd' to claim that Britain was a 'high
price, high profit' market given the decline in the profitability of UK
manufacturers and the severity of the recession.
</TEXT>
