<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Assault on red tape is launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government will examine more than 6,000 pieces of legislation and 2,500
forms as part of its review of red tape affecting businesses, Mr Neil
Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, said yesterday, Charles Batchelor
writes.
At the same time, the Institute of Directors launched a campaign to raise
awareness of the dangers of over-regulation and to promote measures to
reduce burdens on business. Mr Peter Morgan, institute director-general,
said small companies in particular faced a 'systems overload' when dealing
with regulations.
Mr Hamilton told an IoD seminar that government departments were expected to
complete their reviews of business legislation within a few weeks. They will
then assess their impact on business and decide how they can reduce the
burden.
From April departments will carry out a rolling review of regulations to
ensure that pressure is kept up to minimise their impact.
Mr Hamilton will make monthly reports to the prime minister on the
performance of ministries.
Departments often under-estimated the impact of regulations, Mr Hamilton
said. The Home Office had estimated the cost of new fire regulations at
Pounds 1.7bn, but the Association of District Surveyors had calculated the
cost at Pounds 8bn.
