<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Family company mirrors plight of machine tool sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIX MONTHS after the collapse of Beaver Engineering Group focused attention
on the plight of the machine tool industry, 10 designers are almost all that
remains of what was once the sector's largest family-owned company.
Beaver's service and design activities were bought in October by Mikron, the
leading Swiss milling machine producer, in a move that received little
attention beyond the industry and Beaver's home base of Norwich.
The sale was negotiated by Cork Gully, the administrative receivers, and the
terms have not been disclosed. A design team led by Mr Tony Jackson, former
Beaver technical director, will continue designing machining centres -
multi-functional machine tools - at Norwich.
Marketing, service and spare parts activities have been transferred to
Mikron's Birmingham subsidiary, and manufacturing of Beaver machining
centres is being switched to Mikron's plant at Biel in Switzerland, where
there is spare capacity.
When Mikron acquired Beaver the receivers had already cut the workforce by
80 to between 50 and 60. Mr Tony Balding, former managing director and son
of the company's founder, was made redundant in July and has mixed feelings
about the sale.
'If you look at what Beaver was - at one point we had 290 employees - it
does not seem that much has been saved,' he said. 'But Beaver's innovative
capability, or part of it at least, has been retained, and one must hope
that it will be nurtured.'
Beaver, founded in 1951, was one of the most technologically innovative UK
machine tool makers. After expanding in the boom conditions of the late
1980s, it struggled to survive in the recession and foundered when its bank
withdrew support. Mikron was immediately suggested as a possible buyer - the
two companies signed a marketing agreement in the late 1980s and earlier
this year unveiled their first jointly developed machining centre,
This is one of two Beaver machining centres which will be manufactured by
Mikron. The Beaver name will disappear, but Mr Ralph Schmitz-Drager, Mikron
finance director, indicated it might be revived if the Swiss company
developed some of Beaver's other machine tools, such as lathes.
Mr Schmitz-Drager said the prospects for the Beaver machining centres were
good.
The design team is looking for a new 5,000 sq ft office in Norwich - the
current factory is 100,000 sq ft. Mr Balding has set up his own consultancy,
APB Enterprises, and is looking for opportunities to 'keep the wolf from the
door'.
</TEXT>
