FT  10 DEC 92 / Computer services staff to be axed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EDS-SCICON, the computing services company, is planning to make more than
250 people, or 6 per cent of its workforce, redundant following a review of
staffing levels.
It will be one of the largest job-shedding exercises in the computing
services sector and reinforces the view in the information technology
industries that only a weak economic recovery can be expected next year.
Mr Tom Butler, the new managing director, said that on expected levels of
business there were 380 jobs too many in the organisation and only 100
vacancies to be filled.
The workforce was told yesterday that the redundancies would be announced
after a 30-day consultation period. Mr Butler said the redundancies would
involve managers and administrative staff as well as technicians and sales
personnel.
EDS-Scicon was formed by the merger last year between the UK operations of
EDS, a General Motors subsidiary and one of the world's largest computing
services companies, and SD-Scicon. Mr Butler said the redundancies would
involve staff from both sides of the merged company.
The company has substantial expertise in facilities management - running
other companies' computers on a contractual basis. It is expected to be a
prime contender to win contracts under the 'market testing' programme
announced last month by the government.
