FT  10 DEC 92 / Charities given lottery pledge
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SAFEGUARDS will be built into the national lottery to protect charities'
fundraising projects, the government said yesterday.
Mr Robert Key, national heritage minister, said the government had explored
ways of ensuring that charities did not suffer indirectly as a result of the
planned lottery.
These included relaxing laws on small charitable lotteries to make them more
attractive, and the sensitive marketing of the lottery - which would deliver
'tremendous benefits' to charities nationwide.
Charities have warned that their income may drop because of the lottery,
which will have a weekly jackpot of Pounds 1m.
At the same time they feared suffering if lottery adverts focused on other
individual charities as the latest 'good cause'.
Mr Key said the charities' concerns had been taken on board in drafting the
Lottery Bill, and he told the National Council for Voluntary Organisations
that there would be a separate mechanism for distributing lottery money to
charities.
He said: 'The onus will be on getting the product right - not on exploiting
this month's good cause.'
Art treasures could be loaned to regional museums if the government
allocated a Pounds 1m annual grant, Sir David Wilson, former director of the
British Museum, said.
He said requests for temporary collections were becoming more frequent, but
the costs of security, transport and care often made lending impossible.
In an open letter to Mr Peter Brooke, heritage secretary, Sir David suggests
that if regional venues 'were allowed an annual sum of Pounds 1m, they would
be able to provide access to treasures housed in national museums on a scale
never previously realised'.
