<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SENATOR Max Baucus, chairman of the Senate trade subcommittee, called on the
Bush administration yesterday to halt the Uruguay Round of trade talks
'until the Clinton team is fully consulted and has input on the
negotiations'.
The senator, who has advised President-elect Bill Clinton on other trade
matters, said that, because the recently concluded US-EC oilseeds agreement
was 'almost meaningless', he had 'no faith in the ability and willingness'
of the Bush administration to conclude agreements in other areas.
Mr Clinton has indicated his support for continued negotiations by the Bush
administration.
But his supporters are divided on the issue of trade, between those who want
to see the Uruguay Round finished swiftly and those who want Mr Clinton to
take office and make significant changes in a compromise text introduced by
Mr Arthur Dunkel, director-general of Gatt, which is now the basis for
negotiation.
Senator Baucus said the text was not acceptable to Congress as it endangered
domestic trade laws, 'does little' on intellectual property rights, and
'potentially exposes US environmental laws to unwarranted challenge'.
