<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / World Trade News: Swiss No to closer ties leaves Efta
picking up the pieces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE resounding Swiss No to the European Economic Area, the free trade zone
linking the EC's 12 members with the seven countries of the European Free
Trade Association, has left Efta facing every which way. The association,
which holds its regular autumn meeting in Geneva today and tomorrow, has the
task of sorting out how the EEA can be realised without Switzerland, and
agreeing a common approach to the European Community.
In the longer term the Swiss decision has injected more uncertainty into the
debate over Efta's long-term future and its relationship with third
countries, especially in central and eastern Europe.
The EEA, which was due to come into force on January 1, is certain to be
delayed by a few months - or more, if Swiss withdrawal entails renegotiation
of the accord's terms.
Switzerland, as Efta's richest member, was due to pay the most - SFr350m
(Pounds 160.5m) over five years - into an Efta cohesion fund for the benefit
of poorer EC regions. Simply deducting the Swiss contribution could provoke
demands by Spain and other southern European states for a compensating
concession elsewhere in the EEA agreement.
To maintain the fund would mean higher contributions by Austria, Finland,
Iceland, Norway and Sweden, the remaining members, assuming Liechtenstein
follows Switzerland in voting No this weekend. Alternatively, Switzerland
could pay its contribution anyway, in the hope of persuading the EC to look
kindly on individual bilateral deals that will ease Swiss trade with the EEA
area.
Mr Jean-Pascal Delamuraz, the Swiss trade and economy minister, will come
under pressure at the meeting to indicate Swiss intentions. Embarrassingly,
Switzerland is due to assume the rotating Efta presidency for the first half
of 1993.
There could also be problems in financing the new competition body and court
of justice Efta is setting up to administer its side of the EEA treaty,
which will double Efta's annual budget to about SFr100m.
The Swiss government has not yet made up its mind whether to press ahead
with its application to join the EC - alongside Austria, Finland, Norway and
Sweden. However, the most likely prospect two or three years from now is for
a shrunken Efta comprising Switzerland, Iceland and Liechtenstein, with only
Iceland in need of Efta's EEA superstructure.
That is unless they invite central and eastern European countries to join
them. These nations could see Efta as a convenient vehicle for EEA entry and
a means to accelerate eventual EC membership.
Efta has set up links of varying closeness with several states in the
region, largely paralleling accords these countries have with the EC.
Efta ministers will today sign agreements on free trade in industrial and
processed agricultural goods with Poland and Romania and a declaration of
co-operation with Albania. The association's free trade accord with the
Czech and Slovak Republics came into force in July.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
