FT  10 DEC 92 / World Trade News: European chemicals have 'last chance'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPE'S petrochemical industry has one last chance to rationalise itself to
avoid a disorderly and disastrous restructuring during the next down-cycle,
Mr Michael Bennett, a director at the consultants Arthur D. Little, warned
yesterday.
He said at the FT's petrochemical conference in London that the European
industry had to rationalise to make itself globally competitive.
The main threat to European producers remains Asian output, which is set to
increase rapidly. Mr Mohammed Al-Kathiri, general manager of Sabic Marketing
in Europe, said that by the year 2000 34 per cent of petrochemical demand
would be in the Asia-Pacific region, 28 per cent in western Europe and 24
per cent in the US.
Mr Pramote Chaiyavech, technical director of Thailand's National
Petrochemical Corp, who called on European companies to invest in the
region, predicted annual south-east Asian ethylene production would increase
from 915,000 tonnes a year in 1992 to 2.4bn by the end of the decade. The
region has benefited from advantageous gas feed stocks.
North-east Asian capacity was expanding faster than regional demand, but
might be saved by rapid growth in China, the region's largest potential
market, Mr Al-Kathiri said. This could suck in capacity from Korea and the
Middle East.
New 'star' petrochemical products included methyl tertiary butyl ether
(MTBE) and PTA, said Mr Reynaldo Ortiz, petrochemical division manager at
International Finance Corp. He warned that markets for other overnight
wonders had quickly suffered from overcapacity.
Public trust in the industry had fallen steeply over the past decade, warned
Mr James Lindhelm, chairman of Burson-Marsteller Europe. The industry had to
improve its environmental performance.
</TEXT>
