FT  10 DEC 92 / World Trade News: Japan waves anti-dumping stick at China
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN has warned that anti-dumping duties may be imposed on Chinese
exporters of ferrosilicon manganese, used by the steel industry, unless they
increase prices alleged to be unfairly low.
Officials at Japan's Ministry of International Trade and Industry denied
local newspaper reports that a decision had already been made to apply
duties of between 5 and 26 per cent, which would be the first anti-dumping
penalties imposed by Japan.
However, Japanese investigators have warned Chinese export corporations that
there is evidence of unfair pricing policies which have caused damage to
Japanese producers, and that further information will be sought before a
final decision. China's share of the Japanese market has risen from about 17
per cent in 1989 to 39 per cent.
Reports of the anti-dumping case are embarrassing for Japan, which has taken
a leading role in international negotiations on the anti-dumping issue. It
recently produced a discussion paper which concluded that a series of
European cases against Japanese producers were unfairly conducted.
The case highlights increasing trade tensions between Japan and China, whose
exporters are penetrating a range of markets, prompting complaints from
local producers. Japanese textile companies also complain that Chinese
factories are using predatory pricing policies to gain market share.
An investigation was made of ferrosilicon manganese producers in South
Africa and Norway, but it is believed that both countries will be cleared of
dumping. Japanese officials were required to prove unfair pricing and that
domestic producers suffered as a result of that pricing.
In the past, Japan had threatened to impose anti-dumping duties on South
Korean knitwear exporters, but these companies reluctantly agreed to
'voluntary restraints' before the duties were formally imposed, and Tokyo is
hoping that a similar agreement will be reached with the Chinese producers.
About seven Chinese state-run companies are alleged to price exports at far
below levels offered on the domestic market, but the companies insist they
are doing nothing wrong. Miti officials said they were gathering further
information from the companies, and negotiations would continue into the New
Year.
</TEXT>
