FT  10 DEC 92 / Italy approves despatch of troops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM and STEVEN BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME, TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Italian cabinet yesterday approved despatch of 2,500 servicemen to
Somalia at the request of the UN and US, with 1,200 troops to support UN
humanitarian operations in Mozambique, Robert Graham reports from Rome.
Most of the contingent will arrive in Somalia by boat and should be fully
operational by January 4. The US is said to have sought Italy's military
presence given its colonial links with Somalia and knowledge of the factions
in the civil war. Rome is keen to prove its international role and
leadership of Nato's southern flank rapid intervention force.
Steven Butler reports from Tokyo: Japan is considering whether to contribute
financially to UN-backed relief efforts in Somalia, Mr Koichi Kato, chief
cabinet secretary, said yesterday.
His comments were the strongest indication yet that Japan would back the
effort, although Tokyo may still be vulnerable to criticism that its
response was late and inadequate. Its slow reaction is thought to have
damaged its chances of becoming a permanent member of the UN Security
Council.
It was still too early to discuss the size of a Japanese contribution, Mr
Kato added, but Japan faced no constitutional barriers to supporting this
humanitarian effort. Tokyo might provide medical aid and refugee relief, and
would consider sending personnel. There would be little public support for
Japan's sending troops to Somalia.
