<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / US Marines make first easy inroads in Somalia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOGADISHU
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IN A convoy of 22 armoured personnel carriers and anti-tank vehicles, more
than 200 Marines weighted down with weaponry and dressed in desert fatigues
yesterday made a full-scale assault on the wreckage of the former US Embassy
compound.
Cobra helicopter gunships hovered overhead as the nervous Marines fanned out
across the vast Embassy grounds and advanced on the vandalised buildings.
US soldiers two years ago had to pluck US diplomats and foreigners from the
rooftop to safety as Somalia slipped into anarchy and the US turned its back
on its former cold war satellite.
On that occasion the Marines faced gunfire, tracer bullets and anti-aircraft
flak. Yesterday the only obstacles were cows and goats grazing on the
overgrown garden littered with the rusting innards of computers, fax
machines and filing cabinets - the debris of repeated looting.
At the airport yesterday Marines searched buildings, shouted orders in
English at sleeping workers in an airport hangar and forced them to lie face
down with their hands spread out on the tarmac. One worker had his left arm
in the air bent at right-angles. For several minutes US soldiers shouted at
him until a fellow worker explained in broken English that the man's arm was
broken.
At the port helicopters fired tracer bullets over reporters and port workers
as soaked Marines arrived. The US later claimed they had been fired at
first. 'They started firing at us on three different occasions. We returned
fire,' Captain David Clement, 33, whose Fox company from the Ninth Marines
Regiment landed in 18 Zodiac inflatable dinghies.
Somali drivers and guards were arrested and had their hands tied behind
their backs with plastic handcuffs. Their guns, used to protect their
vehicles from bandits, were temporarily confiscated.
The Marines were clearly confused and many said they were scared. They
dropped boxes of ammunition and other equipment in the first hour of the
operation to secure the port, a hub of the relief effort.
Later, bandits known as moriyan fired on a vehicle belonging to an aid
agency injuring two men. The men's colleagues later blamed the Americans,
who they said had confiscated 12 of their guns.
Col Fred Peck, the Marine spokesman, yesterday defended the strong-arm
tactics. 'We did it to make a point,' he said. 'We are here and we are here
for serious business.' Many of the senior Marine officers, like Col Peck,
are well acquainted with Somalia's problems but it was clear yesterday that
most Marines have a poor understanding of Somalia. 'We didn't know you have
to move around the city with gunmen,' one soldier said.
While yesterday's lightning operation passed off remarkably successfully,
and crowds welcomed the Americans they see as their deliverers, Somalis say
the US should proceed sensitively in the coming days. Negotiations with
local warlords, so far ignored, will have to proceed smoothly.
The experience of the Marines in Lebanon a decade ago ought to provide a
cautionary tale.
When they first landed in Beirut they were greeted with euphoria as saviours
from the warlords and rival militias. As soon as they got bogged in Lebanese
politics that euphoria quickly turned to hostility, and 241 Marines returned
home in body bags before they evacuated the city. Somalia is not Lebanon.
The rival clan-militias are not as heavily armed or motivated. But there are
parallels. Even the US flag raised over the embassy yesterday was the same
one that flew over the Marine barracks in Beirut.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-2994</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLJCGABEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Secrets charge in Singapore
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Singapore authorities have brought charges against four people in
connection with press reports earlier this year concerning the country's
economic performance, Kieran Cooke writes.
On June 29 Singapore's Business Times newspaper published preliminary
estimates of second quarter growth figures, saying it would be about 4.6-4.8
per cent. The government said the report was based on leaked information and
the internal security department launched an investigation.
Mr Patrick Daniel, the Busines Times editor, is among those charged under
the provisions of Singapore's official secrets act. Also charged are a
senior official at the Monetary Authority of Singapore and two economists
working for Crosby's Securities.
The four were released on bail of SDollars 5,000 (Pounds 1,900) each.
