<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Robust growth in Vietnam economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HO CHI MINH CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Vietnamese economy performed robustly in 1992 despite the disappearance
of Soviet aid and the continuing economic boycott applied by the US since
the Vietnam war, Mr Vo Van Kiet, the prime minister, said yesterday.
In a confident assessment of Vietnam's economic prospects, he told the
National Assembly in Hanoi: '1992 is ending with a relative overall victory
in the economy, the first year we have fulfilled and even surpassed our main
targets.'
He unveiled a string of encouraging statistics: the economy as a whole will
grow an estimated 5.3 per cent this year, with industrial production up
about 15 per cent - a figure which includes growing oil output - and
agricultural production up 4.4 per cent.
Foreign investment will have increased 73 per cent and state revenues also
rose sharply because of more efficient tax collection; inflation has fallen
to about 15 per cent; and the local currency has stabilised following harsh
restrictions on the money supply.
Mr Vo Van Kiet attributed the strength of the economy to the policy of doi
moi or renovation, the Vietnamese version of perestroika since the late
1980s, although he acknowledged that much more needed to be done.
The current session of the National Assembly is not only revising foreign
investment regulations to attract further inflows of foreign capital but is
focusing on the problem of smuggling and official corruption. The government
would seek to stop bureaucrats wasting money.
The prime minister accepted the need for foreign borrowing to finance
badly-needed construction and repair of power stations, ports and roads.
But he said debt arrears had to be paid off and outlined a cautious approach
to future borrowing. 'We should not borrow to finance our day-to-day
spending,' he declared.
The Vietnamese government, with Vietnamese and American businesses, is
anxious for the US to lift or at least relax its economic embargo before
President George Bush leaves office in January.
Vietnam sees the US as a counterweight to the growing influence of Japan and
China, and is particularly keen to use loans - at present blocked by
Washington - from the World Bank, the International Money Fund and the Asian
Development Bank to pay for infrastructure projects and lay the foundations
for growth.
</TEXT>
