<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Takeshi Noda confirms slowdown of Japanese economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE likelihood of a prolonged slowdown of the Japanese economy was confirmed
yesterday by Mr Takeshi Noda, director-general of the Economic Planning
Agency, who said that Japan would have trouble reaching a 3.5 per cent
growth target in the next fiscal year, starting in April, Steven Butler
reports from Tokyo.
This is the first indication from a senior government minister that Japan's
economy, in the grip of the most severe downturn in nearly 20 years, would
not see strong recovery just around the corner. Mr Noda is the cabinet
minister responsible for monitoring performance of the economy and
co-ordinating economic policy.
Mr Noda said Japan needed to set its 1993 growth target at realistic levels
that would be achieved through policy efforts. Otherwise the government's
credibility would be undermined. Mr Noda's agency, in a monthly report,
yesterday confirmed that the economy remained in the doldrums due to a slump
in personal consumption and a decline in industrial outout.
The government's official growth forecast, which is drawn up for purposes of
fiscal planning, this year remains at 3.5 per cent, although this is
expected to be revised downward in the near future. Many private economists
expect growth to fall below 2 per cent.
The Japanese Diet is expected this week to pass a supplementary budget that
will provide legislative authority for the government's Y10,700bn emergency
economic plan announced in August. A further supplementary budget in the
spring is widely thought necessary in order to restore growth to the
economy.
</TEXT>
