FT  10 DEC 92 / Mexico furious over US drugs accusations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FORMER Mexican interior minister, Mr Manuel Bartlett, has vehemently denied
claims by US federal prosecutors that he was involved in drug-running and in
the 1985 murder of Mr Enrique Camarena, an official of the US Drug
Enforcement Agency.
The accusations were made during the trial of Mr Alvarez Humberto Machain, a
Mexican doctor kidnapped by DEA agents to face charges in the US of aiding
the torture and murder of Mr Camarena.
The fall-out from the allegations may damage relations between the two
countries at a time when Mexico is keen to establish good terms with the
incoming Clinton administration.
US prosecutors accused Mr Bartlett, Mr Enrique Alvarez de Castillo, former
attorney-general, and Mr Juan Arevala, former defence minister, of accepting
money from the Guadalajara drugs cartel. They also claimed that some of them
were present at meetings in which Mr Camarena's murder was planned.
Mr Bartlett, governor-elect of the state of Pueblo, was education minister
until this year, and interior minister throughout former President Miguel de
la Madrid's administration. In the latter post he oversaw the controversial
1988 presidential elections that brought Mr Carlos Salinas to power. The
president may thus go to some lengths to protect him.
The US accusations drew a furious response from the Mexican government,
already incensed at the kidnapping of Mr Machain.
'The prosecution has acted irresponsibly and immorally to involve people who
have held important public offices based on the testimony of delinquents and
criminals who do not merit credibility in light of their personal history,'
the attorney-general's office said.
Mexico also condemned Mr Machain's kidnap as contrary to international law,
and an infringement of its national sovereignty. It thus argues that his
trial is itself illegal.
