<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / West regrets Gaidar's rejection: Vote against acting PM seen
as blow to debt relief talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE rejection of Mr Yegor Gaidar as Russia's acting prime minister and
guardian of the economic reform process is seen as a serious setback to
western efforts to negotiate further debt relief and financial support for
President Boris Yeltsin's government.
Officials in European capitals made it clear that the upheaval in Moscow is
seen with grave concern. 'Nobody can be happy,' one said. 'Naturally it does
not help relationships to dismiss such a key man at such a sensitive moment.
What is needed now above all else is continuity, and a calm but decisive
hand.'
A Bonn Finance Ministry spokesman added: 'We also need continuity as a
signal to the west that Russia will meet its commitments, in exchange for
international co-operation.'
'We hope and assume that the discussion on the reform process in Russia will
continue, regardless of personnel decisions. We hope that happens, in the
interests of Russia and its population, and for the success of the
restructuring process.'
Senior German officials are seeking to finalise agreements before next week,
when Chancellor Helmut Kohl visits Moscow for his first top-level talks
since the departure of Mr Mikhail Gorbachev and end of the Soviet Union.
In Washington, Senator Sam Nunn, the influential Georgia Democrat who chairs
the Senate armed services committee, said Mr Gaidar's rejection would be 'a
blow to Yeltsin and a blow to economic reform.' After a meeting with
President George Bush he said: 'There are other people who believe just as
fervently in the market economy as Gaidar, but he is now the symbol.'
Senator Richard Lugar, the senior Republican on the Senate foreign relations
committee, said he believed President Yeltsin wanted to maintain both the
path of economic reform and Mr Gaidar, and might want to work out some way
in which the latter could 'continue to be effective.'
For his part, Mr Gaidar appeared sanguine. 'I think that the government
should carry on calmly,' he said. Others agreed with him. Mr Vladimir
Ispravnikov, chairman of the Supreme Economic Council of the Russian
parliament, said there 'was nothing terrible for Gaidar in this: he'll stay
as acting prime minister and the president will take responsibility for
him.'
Some even interpreted the vote to reject Mr Gaidar as a victory for him. His
political adviser, Mr Vladimir Mau, said: 'The vote confirms Gaidar as a
major political figure. We didn't expect anything like half. No other
candidate could have got as much.'
Although the votes were not recorded, it was clear that hardline groups of
nationalists and communists, such as Russian Unity, had voted against Mr
Gaidar coupled with so-called centrist factions such as the Industrial
Union, Smena and Agrarian Union.
However, the substantial vote for the prime minister means that the core
pro-government constituencies - the Parliamentary Reform Coalition - in the
Congress estimated yesterday to be between 300 and 350 deputies, has been
swollen by members from at least some of the centrist groups.
</TEXT>
