FT  10 DEC 92 / EC approves pounds 364m of aid for former Soviet Union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission yesterday approved Ecu450m (Pounds 364m) of aid to
the former Soviet Union, including Ecu100m for programmes to improve nuclear
safety, writes Lionel Barber from Brussels.
Russia is the largest beneficiary, with one quarter of the aid focused in
the regions of St Petersburg, Moscow, Samara and Tyumen, mainly on helping
businesses in food production, distribution and energy.
Ukraine will receive Ecu48m. The Caucasian states - comprising Georgia,
Armenia and Azerbaijan - as well as the Central Asian states, including
Kazakhstan, will receive technical aid worth Ecu57.4m.
The EC money comes through the Tacis programme whose long-term goal is to
use technical aid to help the nascent private sector and build up a market
economy in the former Soviet republics.
Last year, the EC committed Ecu400m to the newly independent states.
