<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Russian government prepares for walk-on role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Russian government met last night fully expecting to be asked to
continue for three months in an acting capacity.
Its daily companion, the economic crisis, will also continue, though in a
more permanent capacity.
In that sense, the Seventh Congress of Peoples' Deputies, which yesterday
failed to confirm the appointment of Mr Yegor Gaidar as prime minister, has
changed nothing fundamental yet.
Mr Boris Yeltsin, the Russian president, and Mr Gaidar, the acting prime
minister, offered important concessions to get support for Mr Gaidar's
appointment from the Congress centre - concessions of people and policies.
It was understood last night that those concessions will remain.
The personnel changes started in November, when in quick succession Mr
Yeltsin relieved Mr Yegor Yakovlev of his post as head of the Commonwealth
TV service, Mr Mikhail Poltoranin of his post as information minister and
moved Mr Gennady Burbulis from the post of state secretary to that of chief
adviser.
These were seen as bowing to the wishes of the centrist Civic Union bloc
with whom he wished to make an agreement: though in fact, Mr Yakovlev was an
appointee of Mr Mikhail Gorbachev with no secure base in the Yeltsin
nomenklatura, Mr Burbulis suffered no appreciable loss of power and Mr
Poltoranin is likely to get another high-level job soon.
As compromises they were fairly small beer.
The deal offered by Mr Yeltsin on Tuesday was a grander affair. To persuade
the deputies to vote for Mr Gaidar, he proposed that the Supreme Soviet, the
standing parliament, would have the right to confirm four ministers apart
from the premier - defence, foreign affairs, interior and security. This put
the unpopularly liberal Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the foreign minister, directly in
the firing line: he was to be a sacrifice for the preservation of Mr Gaidar.
Mr Gaidar said yesterday there would be further changes in the cabinet - but
stressed that this would be on the grounds of ability, not because others
wanted their jobs. 'The past year, he said, 'has shown that not everyone in
the cabinet can cope with their responsibilities.' The policy changes are
potentially more serious. In the last few days, Mr Gaidar or Mr Yeltsin have
promised a long delay in rises in the oil price to world levels, the
indexing of the billions of roubles in personal savings and an end to the
decline in production and living standards.
Underpinning their new policy is a document which has been agreed between
the government and the Civic Union. Called 'Urgent Measures to Take Russia
out of its Crisis', it is in effect an agreement for the government to
protect, promote and support Russian industry: in its key phrase, to conduct
a 'managed transition' to the market economy.
In part, this policy is already in place. Russian companies are protected by
fantastically cheap inputs, though their low quality of output means they
have not yet capitalised on this - and on the undervalued rouble - by
exporting much.
The policy also allows for the pumping of credits, more or less
indiscriminately, into enterprises, good and bad. As Mr Gaidar put it
yesterday, he wished to give the crisis 'a more structural character': that
is, he wants the credits to go to the winners, and the losers to go to the
wall.
It is a policy on which a compromise with the industrialists can be based.
But it is not, according to the foreign financial experts in Moscow, a
policy for financial stability. Nor, on the face of it, will it help to get
inflation down to 2 per cent a week (from 4 per cent) as Mr Gaidar promised
yesterday.
Mr Yeltsin, Mr Gaidar and his cabinet all stress that inflation, and the
fear of hyperinflation, is their main concern: but if it is, they have, as
yet, no explicit programme for combating it.
No government could survive, unpunished, with such a record as Mr Gaidar's
in a fully functioning democracy: the fact that the votes for and against
yesterday were so evenly balanced showed that he had won over part of the
centre. (There is even the prospect that his premiership might be proposed
over and over again until he wins.)
Meanwhile, the government is, as it well knows, saddled with the task of
allowing most things to get worse in order to clear the space for them to
get better. And the Congress has neither been able to affect the likelihood
of things getting worse, nor bring forward the time when they will get
better.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
RUSSIAN CONGRESS OF PEOPLE'S DEPUTIES
1060 deputies; 4 main groups; 14 factions
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
THE PARLIAMENTARY REFORM COALITION, the so-called radical democrats, has
251 deputies and firmly supports the Yeltsin-Gaidar government. The
coalition is the successor of the DemRossiya movement which brought
Yeltsin to power.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
THE CENTRE is divided into two groups, both of which overlap with the
Civic Union, an unstable alliance of 'centrist' political figures who
have been negotiating with the government on conditions for supporting
it.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
The Democratic Centre grouping has 200 deputies who represent, among
others, the Unaffiliated Deputies, the Left Centre and the Popular Free
Russia Party (whose honourary chairman is Vice-President Alexander
Rutskoi). This grouping is divided over whether to support the
government and what policy changes to demand. It is closely identified
with the Civic Union.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
The Creative Forces grouping has 151 deputies and represents, among
others, the Industrial Union, a conservative industrialist faction which
is not part of the Civic Union, and Smena (Change of Guard), which is
officially part of the Civic Union but wants a change of government.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
RUSSIAN UNITY has 355 deputies and unites communist and militant
nationalists. It includes factions such as the Communists of Russia and
the Agrarian Union, which embraces the directors of state farms.
Russian Unity virulently opposes the government and its economic reform
programme.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Source: Russian Parliament Press Centre
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
