<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Brussels approves state aid for Fiat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission yesterday approved up to L5,189bn (Pounds 2.5bn) of
state aid for Fiat, the Italian carmaker, one of the largest state subsidies
sanctioned by Brussels in recent years.
The aid is part of a wide-ranging L12,000bn programme of investment by the
Italian group in the depressed Mezzogiorno region of southern Italy,
including the construction of a car plant and an engine plant.
The Commission decided that L10,442bn of investment was eligible for
regional and research subsidies of which it has approved L4,884bn for
regional subsidies and a soft loan of L305bn for research.
Commission officials said yesterday that although Italy was adding capacity
of 450,000 small cars, most of that increase would be offset by capacity
cuts in northern Italy. 'Overall (the plan) adds only 0.2 to EC car
capacity,' said an official, and 3 per cent to Fiat group capacity.
The Commission also judged that the difficulty of opening plants in the
Mezzogiorno and the region's serious economic problems justified a high
level of government aid.
The Commission said that although the investment was being made immediately,
the subsidies would be paid at the end of the project in 1995. The impact
may be diluted to around 30.5 per cent of the eligible expenditure.
The Commission approved aid yesterday of DM260m for a new Opel car plant at
Eisenach in eastern Germany, part of a total investment of DM1.27bn.
</TEXT>
