<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / The Edinburgh Summit: The S word: teach yourself
summit-speak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What is subsidiarity?
The principle - originally a part of Catholic doctrine - that decisions
should be taken at the lowest appropriate level. But this is only one
definition among many. Cynics say subsidiarity means anything and nothing.
Many believe EC leaders at Edinburgh should sort out what the word actually
means before they start deciding how it should be applied.
. . . . and transparency?
Euro-speak for openness. The Community would be more 'transparent' if
policy-makers consulted citizens more often, held more debates in public and
refused to use words like subsidiarity and transparency.
So why do we need these principles?
To bring EC decision-making 'closer to the citizen', according to the
conclusions of the October's Birmingham summit. Member governments and the
Commission believe greater openness will help a disgruntled populace
understand how and why the Community acts. The application of subsidiarity -
or 'nearness' as the leaders described it at Birmingham  - should ensure
that citizens are not vexed by unnecessary EC measures which could be better
handled at national level.
What might be decided at Edinburgh?
Rules for applying subsidiarity: for example, the circumstances in which
member states, rather than the Community, should take responsibility for
telling their citizens what to do. The big member states have also pressed
for the right to put legislation through a subsidiarity test at the draft
stage. These efforts have been resisted by their smaller EC partners who see
this as a way of overriding their ally, the Commission.
It all sounds a bit theoretical - what will this actually mean?
There could be substantive changes to legislation. Some measures may be
scrapped or amended. The Commission and member states have been compiling
hit-lists of existing and proposed EC laws which could be revised or
withdrawn in the interests of subsidiarity. The real argument will be about
the size of the legislative bonfire and what should be on it.
The UK, for example, has suggested that 71 directives should be scrapped,
including some controversial environmental and social affairs legislation.
The Commission has a more modest list of 24.
Will there be any real effort to increase transparency?
Certainly. John Major's idea of televising the opening of the Birmingham
summit was pooh-poohed by fellow leaders, but at Edinburgh they will
consider giving the public 'access' to important policy debates between
ministers - possibly by televising them to journalists.
What are the likely benefits of all this?
Well, if decision-making is made more open and guidelines on subsidiarity
are respected, policy-makers may at least think twice before drafting or
approving unnecessarily intrusive legislation.
. . . . and the risks?
The main risk is that member states will use the subsidiarity principle as a
weapon to fight for national interest, by resisting legislation they do not
like. That could undermine the single market, disarm EC environmental
legislation, much of which has to be centrally policed, or render Community
competition policy toothless.
But at least the process will be out in the open, won't it?
Not entirely. Much of the wheeling and dealing between member states will
still go on behind closed doors - in meetings between senior diplomats in
Brussels, for example, or at so-called 'informal' meetings between
ministers. Policy debates may prove entertaining - although speechifying in
nine languages seems unlikely to top the TV ratings - but the serious
horse-trading will still take place in camera rather than on camera.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-3020</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLJCGAAOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / The Edinburgh Summit: Danish No voters start to wobble
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMMUNITY leaders struggling to find a solution to the Danish problem must
hope that not all Danes are as uncompromising as the middle-aged couple who
run a flower shop in the Copenhagen suburb of Frederiksberg.
'We voted No last time and we'll vote No again. We don't want them deciding
everything for us. We want to stay independent,' says Bodil, who runs the
shop with his wife, Mogens.
The flower shop hardliners underline the difficulties of trying to make
revised Maastricht proposals palatable both to other EC governments and to a
sceptical domestic electorate.
Assuming Denmark can agree at Edinburgh a deal on its Maastricht
reservations, the proposals will have to be passed by another referendum,
probably next May or June, to allow the treaty to take effect.
For the Danish sceptics, the priority is to prevent the bigger EC countries
and the bureaucrats of Brussels from interfering in Danish life.
Other Danes, however, are less trenchant. A sizeable number of people who
said No in the June 2 referendum, when the treaty was rejected by 46,000
votes, are clearly thinking of voting Yes next time. But former Yes voters
who plan to say No next time are very hard to find.
Forecasts of dire problems for the Danish economy if the country again
rejects Maastricht are undoubtedly helping to strengthen the tendency. The
government believes that 100,000 Danish jobs may have been lost as the
result of uncertainty since June.
The Frederiksberg florists' young assistant, ear-ringed and with his hair
knotted at the back, voices a typical waverer's view: 'I voted No in June,'
he says.
'But with all this currency trouble and the unemployment, I'm worried about
what happens to the economy if we vote No again.'
European defence co-operation - a key area where Denmark is seeking a
Maastricht exemption - is another topic of concern.
Ms Heidi Petersen, a 21-year-old office assistant from Roskilde, near
Copenhagen, voted No in June because she was afraid that when she has
children they might one day have to serve in a European defence force.
'If they make it so that we don't have to join a European army, I'll vote
Yes next time,' she says.
However, some currents of opinion are running in the opposite direction. A
pro-Maastricht Copenhagen doctor, who voted for the treaty in June, said he
worried that there would be a second No.
He cited signs of growing nationalism in Denmark, as well as the rest of
Europe, and feared that the upsurge of racialist violence in Germany would
cause many Danes to vote No.
In October, when Denmark's political parties agreed on the special
arrangements they several opinion polls pointed to a substantial majority in
a second referendum.
But a Yes vote would be in danger if this so-called 'national compromise'
breaks down - as it has threatened to do this week after the presentation of
Britain's Maastricht proposals. As the Danish government tries to balance
objections to a tortuous series of amendments to a somewhat ethereal treaty,
the plot at the palace of Holyrood House could easily start to look like a
scene from Hamlet's Elsinore.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
