<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / The Edinburgh Summit: Delors the Euro-militant praises the
British - This is a chance to end the smouldering crisis says EC president
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS supposed to be a tour d'horizon, but Mr Jacques Delors' pre-summit
press conference turned out to be a tour de force, writes Lionel Barber in
Brussels.
In vintage form, the European Commission President yesterday displayed the
combination of intellect and passion which still makes him a force to be
reckoned with when it comes to the future of the EC.
'I am a militant European,' he declared in response to a questioner who
dared ask whether the Danish rejection of Maastricht and the resulting
currency turmoil meant that the process of closer European integration had
reached its high water-mark.
'I hope the process of European construction will continue ..there is no
third way between survival and decline.'
Mr Delors set out the stakes for the leaders and citizens of the EC on the
eve of the Edinburgh summit. It was, he said, a chance to end the
smouldering crisis of recent months.
He urged member states to rally behind the so-called Delors II package which
calls for an increase in the Community budget by the end of the decade well
above a counter-proposal put forward by the UK presidency.
Without proper future funding, the EC would risk a retreat into an ivory
tower, he said. It would turn its back on 70m people in the EC's poorer
rural regions, emasculate the research budget needed to improve European
competitiveness, and kill off hopes of making the Community a serious player
on the global stage, particularly in efforts to help the former communist
countries in eastern Europe.
'At one extreme,' he warned, 'by the year 2000, you could just have a large
single market, anaemic common policies, and just a cheque-writing operation
for the poorer members. That is not acceptable.'
Mr Delors said it was wrong to accept 'mediocre commitments' from member
states with 'short-term budgetary problems' - a side-swipe at Germany, the
traditional paymaster in the EC which has taken a tougher line as a result
of the huge costs of unification.
But Mr Delors remained by and large a team player. He praised the UK draft
on the Danish question as 'extremely subtle', and he signalled support for
early talks on enlargement with Austria, Finland, Sweden, and possibly
Norway, next year - on condition that a budget deal was reached and Denmark
and the UK ratified the Maastricht treaty by summer 1993.
Reuter adds: EC officials yesterday urged Mr Delors to press EC leaders to
step up the fight against racism and neo-Nazi aggression in Europe.
EC inaction was helping to increase neo-Nazi violence against immigrant and
other minority groups and desecration of places of worship and cemeteries,
an open letter to Mr Delors signed by more than 2,500 civil servants said.
'The fight against these actions is not being led with the necessary
determination. This constitutes an indirect encouragement for these neo-Nazi
groups,' they said.
</TEXT>
