<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / The Edinburgh Summit: Wily Mitterrand finds way out of
summit clash over farm subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ISOLATION at an EC summit is not a position to which President Francois
Mitterrand, longest serving of Community leaders, is accustomed.
At one stage, it looked as though France might be placed in the dock at
Edinburgh for its rooted opposition to the EC-US agreement on farm trade in
the Gatt negotia tions.
So, it is with considerable relief that Mr Mitterrand now feels that he has
the active connivance of Chancellor Helmut Kohl, and the passive
acquiescence of Prime Minister John Major, to ensure that the issue will not
figure too high on the Edinburgh agenda.
The odds are that Mr Mitterrand will be satisfied if his fellow leaders
follow their foreign and farm ministers earlier this week in insisting that
the agreement be balanced by progress in areas like services and tariffs.
As the president made clear in an interview with the FT this week, his
bottom line is that no amount of progress in the non-farm aspects of the
Gatt negotiations can compensate for what France feels is an unfair
agricultural bargain with Washington.
But he will not feel forced to make a stand unless Mr Major insists on
hailing the farm agreement in the Edinburgh communique.
Paris is fairly confident that Bonn, in its intensive pre-summit contacts
with London, will have persuaded Mr Major not to push the matter.
But Mr Mitterrand cannot be totally certain of that until this evening, when
he dines with Mr Major in the Scottish capital.
Partly in its bid to win southern European support for its Gatt position,
France is now readier to agree demands by Spain and other poorer EC states
for extra structural economic aid from an enlarged EC budget.
France is the third largest net contributor to the budget, after Germany and
Britain. 'We cannot agree to all that is demanded of us,' said Mr
Mitterrand, 'but we are ready to accept a lot.'
However, there is one French position of principle that could prove awkward
for the UK presidency.
Mr Mitterrand will stress that the richer countries promised more money for
the poorer ones at the Maastricht summit a year ago, and that all the
Maastricht commitments, including, of course, ratification of the treaty,
must be respected.
On this, Mr Mitterrand says he is quite inflexible. He will take a hard line
both against giving any general opt-out from the treaty for Denmark, and
against any appearance by the UK government that it is trying to hide behind
Denmark by delaying the final House of Commons ratification decision until
after a second Danish referendum.
With barely disguised contempt, he said this week: 'I don't see how Great
Britain can submit its decision to another country.'
He added: 'Europe is not stalled. Ten countries out of 12 have ratified. One
country said no. . . Britain is lagging behind and the delay should not be
too lengthy but I have not given up hope of seeing Britain adhere to the
treaty.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
