<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / The Edinburgh Summit: Tide of malaise that threatens to
engulf Major - Ian Davidson strips away the political drama and finds the EC
facing profound historical choices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE British government lives in fear that the European summit it is hosting
in Edinburgh tomorrow and Saturday will turn out to be a total disaster. If
the omens of failure prove true, the Community will be precipitated into a
deep political crisis; and there will be a chorus of denunciation from the
other member states, blaming it all on Britain.
Strictly speaking, such denunciations will be unjustified; they will also be
beside the point. The immediate symptom of the crisis is the rejection of
the Maastricht treaty by the Danish electorate in their referendum last
June. The British government may have made that crisis much worse, by its
prevarication in the House of Commons, and its undisguised dissent from the
underlying objectives of the treaty in Brussels. But in a broader
perspective, it is clear that the looming drama of Edinburgh is really the
symptom of a profound malaise which reaches far deeper, and goes far wider,
than anything which Mr John Major could be expected to devise for good or
ill.
For what is germinating in the European Community is a three-dimensional
crisis in the true meaning of the term; a moment of truth, a decisive choice
point, and possibly a parting of the ways.
The first of these is a crisis about the relationship between the founding
member states and some of the later arrivals; the second is about the
objectives of the Community and how far the integration process can or
should go; the third is about the size of the Community, and whether it can
take in a large number of new members without a profound change in its
character and/or its constitution.
The first is really short-hand for Britain's ambivalence over the purposes
of the European Community as laid down by the original Six. Mr Major says
repeatedly that he wants Britain to be 'at the heart of Europe'; perhaps he
thinks he means it; surely he must see that it is vital for Britain's
future; but it is his misfortune that British ambivalence towards the
Community model of Europe appears to be as visceral and as uncomprehending
today as it was 35 years ago when the then British government declined to
take part in the drafting of the Treaty of Rome.
Some of the newest of today's Twelve, like Spain and Portugal, have become
almost as unconditional in their commitment to Community integration as the
Six founding members. The British, by contrast, have never liked the
integrationist Community devised by the others, and despite 20 years of
membership, they are still trying to turn it into a loose free-trade area.
This unresolved British quarrel with the European Community is now reaching
its climax in the second layer of the three-dimensional crisis, over the
Maastricht treaty. British ministers do not care to be told that their
government does not like this treaty and never has. But there is no getting
away from the fact that the British opt-out from monetary union, described
by Mr Major as a triumphant victory, is not merely a signal diminution of
the British commitment to the objectives of the treaty, but is all of a
piece with those Danish reservations which may yet bring the treaty to
grief.
British ministers consistently minimise the significance of Maastricht, in
some cases going so far as to claim that the treaty will make the Community
less federalist than it would otherwise be. And yet it is hard to reconcile
such minimalism with a treaty whose most conspicuous objectives are monetary
union and a common foreign policy.
The fate of the Maastricht treaty now depends solely on the Danes. For if
they were to get another No, in a second referendum, the British government
would abandon the attempt to ratify it in the House of Commons.
In this uncertainty, British officials talk the double language of
ambivalence. Maastricht is deeply flawed, they say, because it is
intellectually messy, because it is too ambitious in political terms, and
above all because recent events have proved that monetary union is
unworkable. And yet it is essential to ratify the treaty, because that will
avert a crisis, and we shall then be able to reach pragmatic compromises in
the real world.
But the fundamental British interest in ratifying the treaty is that it
would stave off a split in the Community, in which an inner core would move
ahead towards closer economic, monetary and political integration. British
officials are too blase about this. While France and Germany and the Benelux
would undoubtedly prefer the Community to stay together, British officials
translate such a preference into an absolute priority, claiming that France
in particular could not really tolerate a mini-Europe, which would lead to
progressive French subordination to Germany.
This analysis may prove correct; the problem is its British perspective; for
it may underestimate once again the force of the integrationist urge on the
continent, especially between France and Germany. There are obvious
drawbacks in a mini-Europe; but in the past the British have too often paid
the price for assuming that others think the same way as they do.
Finally there is the crisis of Community enlargement, which will move to the
top of the agenda if the Maastricht treaty is ratified. The conventional
wisdom is that the Community can admit new members from Efta without
changing the rules, because they are rich, developed and western European.
Only later, with a subsequent wave of new members, would it be necessary to
rewrite the treaty.
Everyone knows this is Panglossian nonsense. With 16 or 17 members,
decision-making under current arrangements would become virtually
impossible; with 25 it would cease altogether. This issue cannot be
postponed until Poland and Hungary are at the gates, because the admission
of the Finns and the Swedes will determine the institutional terms of the
next enlargement. Yet the Germans insist that enlargement is necessary, and
even the French have now started talking the same way.
The advantage of ratifying Maastricht, from a British perspective, is that
it is one way of shelving the long-standing ideological argument between the
inter-governmentalists and the federalists. The problem is that it opens the
door to what will become a very much larger Community. Such a Community
would certainly need a new constitution, and probably an explicitly federal
constitution at that.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-3027</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLJCGAAHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / The Edinburgh Summit: How ceiling fell in on UK presidency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST countries occupying the rotating presidency of the EC suffer abuse from
their partners; but this year the British have been in a league of their
own.
Over the past five months, UK ministers have been accused of arrogance,
ignorance and sabotage by their European colleagues; the Foreign Office  -
often viewed in Brussels as the most gifted in Europe - finds itself accused
of unprecedented partisanship. The presidency, says one EC observer, is like
a 'Rolls-Royce without a steering wheel'.
Final judgment must await the outcome of the summit. Yet even a success at
Edinburgh will not dispel the question: why has a presidency which was
launched with such high hopes on July 1 attracted such widespread abuse?
There is a respectable argument that Britain has been turned into a
'whipping boy' for all the Community's problems. One anglophile ambassador
in Brussels sums up: 'Number one, Britain did not reject the Maastricht
treaty like Denmark; number two, it did not call an unnecessary referendum
in France, like President Mitterrand; number three, it did not cause the
September crisis in the exchange rate mechanism; and number four it did not
cause the recession.' Others agree that the slowdown in growth has punctured
the EC's self-confidence and weakened political leaders across the
continent.
However tempting it is to paint Britain as a victim of events, other factors
have damaged its cause in Europe. By far the most serious is Britain's delay
in ratifying the Maastricht treaty.
After the razor-thin French approval on September 20, EC leaders thought
they had won a solid commitment from Mr John Major at the Birmingham summit
the following month to press ahead with ratification. His subsequent
concession to a handful of Tory Euro-sceptics to link final ratification of
the treaty to a second Danish referendum was greeted, in the words of an EC
ambassador, 'with total disbelief'.
Mr Major's decision - which was not discussed beforehand with his foreign
secretary, Mr Douglas Hurd - left the British delegation to the EC in
Brussels 'shell-shocked', a UK official recalls. Only days before, British
diplomats had been spreading the word that Mr Major had full cabinet support
for early ratification. 'Major's U-turn destroyed his credibility,' says an
EC diplomat. 'We asked ourselves: how can we believe what he says?'
Some, like Chancellor Helmut Kohl, were more charitable. They accepted the
prime minister's argument that the three-vote margin in the House of Commons
showed how perilously close the government had come to defeat. Others such
as Mr Felipe Gonzalez, Spain's premier, refused to accept the argument that
it was better to make the concession than lose the treaty.
The ratification delay rekindled mistrust in EC capitals about Britain's
attitude to Maastricht, and the Community. Minor instances of ministerial
friction have suddenly become legendary examples of British perfidy.
Last month, Mr Edward Leigh, UK industry minister, unwisely refused to
support calls for further discussion of plans to spend EC money on
high-definition television. He was immediately accused of sabotage by the
Dutch, traditionally Britain's closest ally. Mr Leigh, it appears, forgot
about The Hague's eagerness to help Dutch companies such as Philips profit
from EC funding.
Sir John Cope, UK Paymaster General, is the latest bete noire. His brusque
rejection of the European parliament's additions to EC spending drew howls
of outrage; so did his peevish refusal to countenance any serious discussion
on the British budget rebate.
Similarly, EC finance ministers and central bank governors have yet to
forgive Mr Norman Lamont, UK chancellor of the Exchequer, for using the
presidency for his own ends to press Germany to cut interest rates. He
encouraged colleagues to 'gang up' on the Germans at a finance ministers'
meeting in early September.
Lastly, both diplomats and officials at the European Commission have been
infuriated by the blizzard of paper emanating from Whitehall which has tried
systematically to downgrade the Commission's role.
One EC diplomat describes British resolutions (statements of policy) on
matters such as state aid and subsidiarity (devolving decision-making) as
betraying the old habit of running everything from London.
In the past three weeks, the presidency appears to have learnt some lessons.
The UK paper on Denmark's requests for exemptions on the Maastricht treaty
drew heavily on Mr Jean-Claude Piris, the European Council's chief legal
adviser. Suspicion that the British would produce a 'soft' paper encouraging
the Danes gave way to mild surprise.
If Mr Major can secure deals on the Danish question and the EC budget, he
would confound his critics. But hopes that 1992 would see a shift in
Britain's ambivalence toward the Community have proved unrealistic. Things
might have been easier for Mr Major and the Foreign Office if they had
avoided such suggestions in the first place.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
