<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / The Edinburgh Summit: Paradoxes along the Maastricht road to
Emu
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN WOLF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMIC and monetary union was the most important goal of the treaty of
European Union agreed by leaders of the European Community a year ago at
Maastricht. It is now among the least plausible.
Emu was envisaged as the last of three stages, the first of which was a
'hard' ERM, with universal coverage and few, if any, exchange rate
realignments. The ERM's current disarray may not preclude a move to some
kind of Emu by the end of the century. But it does render almost impossible
the earlier belief in the staged transition to Emu by all, or even most EC
members.
In view of its significance, it is perhaps surprising that strengthening of
the ERM will not be found on the agenda of the Edinburgh summit. This is
supposedly for fear of reviving anxiety in already fragile markets, but
probably because agreement on reform is inconceivable.
The planned path to Emu has become less credible, for three reasons.
First, the treaty has not been ratified and, following the Danish referendum
last June, may never be.
Second, even citizens of the two pivotal countries of the European Community
give far from whole-hearted support to Emu. The French voted in favour of
the Maastricht treaty by the narrowest of margins. A majority of Germans
display marked hostility to the notion of surrendering the D-Mark. The
Bundestag has insisted that it will examine whether the pre-conditions have
been met before Germany moves into any Emu.
Third and most important, after almost six years with only one technical
realignment, two major currencies - the Italian lira and the pound sterling
 -have been forced out of the ERM. The Spanish peseta has been realigned
twice and the Portuguese escudo once. Considerable pressure has also been
imposed upon the Irish punt, the Danish krone and even the French franc. The
ERM is, to the Bundesbank's delight, an adjustable peg exchange rate system
once more. Its most stable element is a D-Mark zone covering Germany, the
Benelux and Austria, which is not even a member of the Community.
Formally, this alteration in the operation of the ERM does not rule out the
Maastricht path to Emu. The treaty demands only that, prior to a decision on
whether it can be included in Emu, each currency should observe 'the normal
fluctuation margins provided for by the ERM for at least two years, without
devaluing against the currency of any other member state'. There is still
time for this requirement to be satisfied.
Nevertheless, the presumption that a hardened ERM would lead smoothly to an
EC-wide Emu has been exploded.
The ERM has gone awry because the European economy has done so. After seven
years of growth in the EC economy at 2.5 per cent a year or more, EC-wide
gross domestic product grew by only 1.3 per cent between 1990 and 1991, is
likely to grow by much the same amount between 1991 and 1992 and again
between 1992 and 1993. Community-wide unemployment has also risen, from 8.4
per cent of the labour force in 1990 to 9.8 per cent in October 1992.
There are three main reasons for the slowdown in the European economy. The
first and least important is what has happened over the past several years
to the global economy, principally to the US. The second reason is 'local
difficulties' in major EC countries, other than Germany, principally too
much private debt in the UK and too much public debt in Italy.
The third and most important reason has been German unification. A real
appreciation of the D-Mark was required, to facilitate absorption of
resources within the German economy. The mistake of the rest of the EC was
to fail to realise the implications of the Bundesbank's refusal to tolerate
higher inflation. A D-Mark realignment or, better still, temporary flotation
of the D-Mark would have been a superior method of bringing about the needed
adjustment than deflation elsewhere in Europe.
The aim of the past three years has been to harden the ERM as a step towards
an Emu that would bind Germany, both politically and economically, into a
European union. The paradoxical outcome has been to weaken the ERM and make
more probable either no Emu at all or a narrow one, totally dominated by
Germany.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
