<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / UK drive to resolve Maastricht deadlock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, LIONEL BARBER and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN led a diplomatic drive yesterday to narrow differences on the Danish
question and the European Community budget in an effort to break the
threatened deadlock at the Edinburgh summit.
The British presidency tabled a new draft plan to meet Danish demands for
opt-outs on the Maastricht treaty and promised a revised budget package
which would channel more resources to the EC's poorer states.
Mr Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission, praised the draft
as 'extremely subtle' which encouraged him to believe that a solution could
be found this week, allowing a second referendum on the Maastricht treaty
next May.
In Bonn, an official said the latest British proposals amounted to 'a very
good basis for a possible solution of the problem', although there were
still 'one or two points to be watched'.
In a pre-summit letter to fellow heads of government, Mr John Major, the
prime minister, voiced optimism that governments 'share a determination to
reach agreement at Edinburgh'.
He said an agreement with Denmark would allow the Community to go ahead
together, adding that the suggested presidency declarations 'do not require
any reopening of the Maastricht treaty, nor, we believe, reratification by
member states'.
A senior EC official cautioned, however, that several member states, notably
Spain, had warned that to enshrine Danish demands in quasi-treaty form would
present constitutional problems which might require reratification of
Maastricht.
Mr Poul Schluter, the Danish prime minister, said the amended British text
'goes a long way to meeting Denmark's wishes'.
'It is a much better paper than the first. The task in Edinburgh is to
achieve a solution. It will be difficult, but I think we shall succeed,' he
said.
But two of the main opposition parties behind Denmark's seven-party national
compromise continued to voice opposition.
Mr Major also offered his opposite numbers revised budget proposals. British
officials said that the plan would retain the UK presidency's suggestion
that the overall increase in Community spending be held to the limits it
outlined earlier this month.
To the fury of Spain in particular, Britain - backed by Germany - has
suggested that the maximum size of the EC budget, the so-called own
resources ceiling, should be raised to 1.25 per cent of EC gross national
product by the end of 1999. That compares with 1.2 per cent at present and
the 1.32 per cent ceiling suggested by the EC Commission.
But the officials said new adjustments to the formula - based on VAT
receipts as well as GDP - under which national governments contribute to the
EC budget, would channel more cash to Spain, Portugal, Greece and Ireland.
So would the allocation to poorer states of uncommitted contingency funds.
It was unclear, however, whether the poorer countries would back the UK
plan. Mr Delors seems certain to oppose it. He appealed for support for his
own financing plan, saying that a restrictive UK compromise on the budget
would emasculate the Community.
In spite of the new proposals, British ministers were last night still
voicing caution on the outcome of the summit.
The prime minister yesterday discussed how the European exchange rate
mechanism could be reformed at a private meeting with trade unionists and
European employers. Downing Street said the government was 'continuing to
look' at possible improvements to the ERM before Britain rejoined.
The UK presidency, Page 2
The Edinburgh menu, Page 3
</TEXT>
