<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / (CORRECTED) Customs queries up as EC change nears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 11th December 1992) appended to this article.
THE Customs and Excise Department has reported a big increase in inquiries
and questions from businesses trading with other EC states before the
abolition of customs frontiers at the beginning of next year.
The tariff and statistical office, which will process a new statistical form
called Intrastat, received more than 3,700 letters and telephone calls
during October and November according to internal estimates.
Nearly three quarters of the responses - about 2 per cent of all EC traders
 -appear not to have been correctly categorised according to the level of
trade that they conduct with other EC states. All those with EC imports or
exports which are valued above Pounds 135,000 a year must complete two new
forms.
The contacts have been prompted by letters sent in October to all 160,000
companies that trade with other EC member states. The letters explained the
procedures for completing the Intrastat form and the EC sales list, a second
form being introduced from the start of the year.
Officials remain confident that they can cope with the administrative
systems required to accompany the creation of the single European market on
January 1.
But the responses suggest widespread ignorance among companies of the
administrative procedures that they must comply with, and a number of
technical hitches in the classification of some of them.
Twelve per cent of respondents were not aware of what Intrastat or the sales
list were, and 43 per cent objected in principle to the idea behind them.
CORRECTION
THE FT of December 9 stated that 43 per cent of a sample of 3,700 traders
contacting the tariff and statistical office of HM Customs &amp; Excise had
objected to Intrastat, the new trade statistics system. This should have
said 43 businesses.
</TEXT>
