<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Late buying takes prices to
new highs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
After trading in a narrow range for most of the day, a burst of late buying
took US share prices to new highs yesterday, writes Patrick Harverson in New
York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 14.85 at 3,322.18,
having spent the best part of the day no more than a few points either side
of Monday's close. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's rose 1.66 to
436.97, a new record, while the Amex composite added 0.29 to 394.65 and the
Nasdaq composite rose 0.59 to 667.12, another new all-time high. Turnover on
the NYSE was heavy at 235m shares, and declines outpaced rises by 994 to
821.
Enthusiasm was dampened in early trading by rumours that Germany might raise
interest rates. Although economists do not believe the Bundesbank would
raise rates, the rumours supported the view that German interest rates are
not likely to fall in the near future.
Otherwise, trading was dominated by technical considerations in the absence
of any domestic economic data. Following recent gains the market looked
slightly overbought, but underlying sentiment remained positive throughout
the day, and aided by a late surge in demand which some traders said was
linked to activity in the futures pits, shares put in another solid
performance. Boeing eased Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 34 5/8 in turnover of
almost 1m shares amid growing concern that the aircraft manufacturer would
be hit by industrial action following Monday night's vote by the Seattle
Professional Engineering Employees Association to reject a three-year
contract from Boeing. Talks were scheduled yesterday between management and
unions.
IBM fell Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 65 3/8 in busy trading after Merrill Lynch,
the broking house, warned that the computer maker might have to take
additional charges in the fourth quarter.
Various big stocks reacted to some late earnings reports. HJ Heinz firmed
Dollars 1 to Dollars 44 1/8 after announcing fiscal second quarter profits
of Dollars 154.2m, up from Dollars 122.8m at the same stage a year ago.
Deere&amp;Co jumped Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 39 5/8 on news that the
agricultural equipment manufacturer earned Dollars 37.4m in the fourth
quarter ended October 31, a substantial turnround from the Dollars 20.2m
loss incurred at the same stage of 1991 (although that was affected by big
restructuring charges).
Times Mirror fell Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 30 3/4 on news that it expected to
take special charges against its fourth quarter earnings to cover costs
related to a restructuring at its Matthew Bender unit, a voluntary
separation programme at the Los Angeles Times, and changes in accounting
procedures.
General Motors climbed Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 34 3/4 in turnover of 2.4m
shares after Kidder, Peabody, the broker, reiterated its 'buy'
recommendation and said the stock was due for a significant upward move over
the next few months.
Canada
TORONTO share prices ended mixed in continued heavy trading.
Based on preliminary data, the TSE 300-stock composite index lost 2.23
points, or 0.07 per cent, to 3,290.86, with declining issues ahead of
advances 340 to 277. Volume surged to 49,237,000 shares worth CDollars
456.1m.
