<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Anglo to invest in Chilean mine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE CRAWFORD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SANTIAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MINERA Mantos Blancos, the Chilean copper mine controlled by Anglo American
of South Africa, plans to invest Dollars 290m over the next five years to
maintain production at its existing mine and develop a new deposit.
Mantos Blancos needs to double the girth of its open-pit mine near
Antofagasta in the Atacama desert to reach the ore body's remaining
reserves. The expansion, which is expected to cost Dollars 85m, will extend
the life of the mine beyond the year 2010. Output is expected to remain
steady at about 75,000 tonnes a year.
The company will also invest Dollars 56m to switch production from copper
oxides to copper cathodes, which are more environment-friendly.
In addition, Mantos Blancos is developing a second ore body called
Mantoverde, which is expected to enter production in 1994 with an annual
output of nearly 40,000 tonnes. Mr Ricardo Martinez, Mantos Blancos'
spokesman, says the company is still studying its funding options.
Mantos Blancos will have to find Dollars 92m to pay for its share of the
Collahuasi copper project should Royal Dutch/Shell and Falconbridge accept
Minorco and Mantos Blancos as their new partners. Minorco, the
Luxembourg-based associate of Anglo American, has made a Dollars 185m bid
for Chevron's 33 per cent stake.
</TEXT>
