<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / Video sales help Carlton rise 15%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CARLTON Communications, the television and film services company, yesterday
announced a 15 per cent profits increase helped by strong sales of video
cassettes, especially in the US.
Pre-tax profits rose from Pounds 88.3m to Pounds 102.3m in the year to
September 30. Mr Michael Green, chairman, described the performance as 'good
progress in a tough year'.
The results were in line with stock market expectations, although the shares
slipped 2p to 717p on light profit-taking. Analysts expect Carlton, which
takes over the London weekday TV franchise from Thames on January 1, to make
profits of about Pounds 128m this year.
Video and audio production and distribution lifted profits 49.8 per cent to
Pounds 46.6m. Video cassette production for customers such as Walt Disney
and Warner grew strongly in line with the US 'sell through' market.
Pickwick, the European video and budget music distributor acquired in
February, contributed Pounds 1m of operating profit on Pounds 42m of sales,
although this did not include the busy Christmas season.
The television and film services division was affected by high average US
dollar exchange rates at its Technicolor film processing subsidiary. Profits
fell from Pounds 28.4m to Pounds 25.1m.
Video and sound products, which includes specialist production equipment
sales to the TV industry, continued to recover and increased profits 39 per
cent to Pounds 19.4m.
Carlton's net cash balance declined from Pounds 162.6m to Pounds 108.5m due
to increased working capital needs and investments. Net interest earnings
fell from Pounds 17.9m to Pounds 10.5m. Profits from associates, mainly a 20
per cent stake in Central independent TV, increased from Pounds 2.8m to
Pounds 6.69m.
Operating costs of Pounds 12.7m incurred by Carlton TV were deferred until
the station begins broadcasting.
Group turnover excluding associates increased 18 per cent to Pounds 635.2m.
At the interim stage, turnover was 13 per cent higher at Pounds 324.7m while
pre-tax profits grew 7 per cent to Pounds 49.4m.
Earnings per share increased 15.5 per cent to 34.2p. A final dividend of
10.3p is proposed to raise the total for the year by 10 per cent to 17p.
