FT  09 DEC 92 / Deutsche Bank bucks trend with 5% fall in profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DEUTSCHE BANK, Germany's largest bank, yesterday reported group operating
profits down by 5 per cent in the first 10 months of the year. The fall was
worse than analysts' expectations and contrasted sharply with the robust
figures of Deutsche's competitors.
It prompted Deutsche's share price to fall by DM13.9 to DM653.1, helping to
drag the DAX index of 30 leading German shares down by 17.08 to 1,508.24.
Total operating profits fell from DM5.20bn to DM4.94bn (Pounds 1.9bn) while
partial operating profit, which excludes the bank's own account trading,
dropped 3.8 per cent to DM3.96bn.
The fall contrasts with reported growth of 16.6 per cent in total operating
profits at Dresdner Bank, Germany's second biggest bank, of 13.3 per cent at
Commerzbank, the third largest bank, 13.2 per cent at the Bayerische
Hypotheken und Wechsel-Bank and more than 20 per cent at Bayerische
Vereinsbank.
Mr Hilmar Kopper, chief executive, said net profits for the full year would
be at least as good as they were last year.
He said Deutsche Bank's profits were bigger than those of the next three
competitors put together and insisted the relative strength of the bank
would become clear at the full-year stage after provisioning for bad debts.
Last year net profits rose from DM1.07bn to DM1.41bn while operating profits
rose 16 per cent to a record DM5.97bn.
A fall in profits was expected after Deutsche's interim profits fell 3.2 per
cent after six months. The bank said then that its size meant that it felt
the slowdown of the German economy earlier than its competitors.
Mr Kopper blamed a shift in revenue mix toward lower margin interbank
business for the profits fall. Other factors were lower trading profits
together with the effect of the appreciation of the D-Mark against other
currencies. Analysts also blamed a lower return on bank lending to eastern
Germany.
Total credit grew 5.7 per cent to DM316.7bn, while net interest income rose
4.2 per cent to DM9.10bn; net interest margins dropped 10 basis points to
2.31 per cent. Commission income rose 7.2 per cent to DM3.39bn.
Mr Kopper said staff numbers would probably drop by 1,000 over the course of
the year.
