<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / House scheme fails to benefit lenders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSES REPOSSESSED by mortgage lenders accounted for only a tenth of the
properties bought by housing associations in the first week of the
government's Pounds 750m scheme to revive the housing market, it was
disclosed yesterday.
The poor initial result for building societies came in spite of their having
lobbied the government to encourage housing associations to buy repossessed
homes rather than unsold ones built by construction and property companies.
When the scheme was ann-ounced in the Autumn Statement by Mr Norman Lamont,
the chancellor, he said it would reduce the overhang of empty properties by
more than 20,000 over the next few months, and provide 'a helpful stimulus
to activity'.
The first week's figures cover only 194 of the 16,000 homes to be bought in
England by next March. But societies said sales would continue to be
restricted by their statutory obligation to seek the highest price and by
the poor condition of many repossessed properties.
In the first week, the 27 associations selected by the Housing Corporation
to make bids applied for approval to buy 19 repossessions, 99 homes
completed by builders and developers, and 76 houses owned by individuals.
Mr Gregory Lomax, deputy chief executive of the corporation, the
government-funded agency which oversees housing associations in England,
said it was trying to encourage them to buy repossessed properties and homes
owned by individuals rather than relying on builders.
He said the corporation had retained 25 per cent of the Pounds 577m
provision for England to reward associations buying from sources other than
builders.
'We are trying to revive the housing market, not to revive the lenders. They
are important, but subsidiary,' he said. Mr Lomax said he expected lenders
to sell more houses through the scheme as they responded to associations'
requirements.
Bedfordshire Pilgrims Housing Association, the association which has spent
its allocation in England the fastest, said it found societies 'slow on the
uptake' in providing lists of repossessions and responding to offers. The
association said it had already allocated all of its initial funding of
Pounds 3.7m in principle. About a quarter of the purchases were from
builders, a quarter from mortgage lenders and the remaining half from
private individuals.
Mr John Wriglesworth, building societies analyst at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew,
said many repossessed properties were not suitable for associations because
they were in bad condition.
</TEXT>
