FT  09 DEC 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The growing use of guns in British crime is widely acknowledged, but were
you aware of 'an alarming increase in drugs-related gun violence among
Britain's African-Caribbean community' ? It is the sort of matter which is
nervously skirted by politically correct current affairs people for fear of
being seen as racist. Good old Open Space, however, BBC2's access slot, has
an account by Sheldon 'Curfew' Thomas, member of a group of rap and reggae
artists, who calls for action to curb this black-on-black violence (7.40).
Today's Bookmark sounds like a collector's item. Poets read their work on
the subject of love and reflect upon the phenomenon. It seems that Hugo
Williams' wife finds his poems 'ludicrous ..but she's French', and Wendy
Cope does not think she will ever stop falling in love, often with other
poets (8.10 BBC2). Dispatches is very excited about the degree of access it
achieved in making today's programme about Britain's presidency of the EC,
seen partly from the inside of the Foreign Office and even from within a
cabinet committee. It promises to be a timely report given that it is now
only two days before the Edinburgh summit (9.00 C4).
