<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / Prepared for worst at any time: The businessman
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Michael Winterflood, managing director, Cannon Steels, structural steel
fabricator, north London.
'We have definitely put off decisions. Anything could happen for the worse
at any time. I certainly can't see it changing for the better. What we have
got now is what we have to live with. We are never going to see the 1980s
again.
'We aren't going to take on any more labour. There was a time when we made
long-term decisions, but at the moment we will book a Christmas drink and
that is about it.
The one thing that would help is the one thing the government can't do - and
that is to promise not to put interest rates back up again now. No one
believes that they won't. I can just see Norman Lamont appearing on the
steps of the Treasury in two years' time to explain why they have reversed
the cuts.
'I don't think people are convinced by the latest reductions. I'm sure they
were done in good faith, but people don't think they will still be this low
in two years' time. If you knew rates would stay put, you might consider
buying that new machine or taking on that extra worker.
'People are not ambitious any more. All they want to do is preserve what
they have got. They look at people speeding ahead and think they will soon
come a cropper.'
</TEXT>
