FT  09 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Extra help promised for jobless
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TOTAL OF 60,000 career development loans are to be made available over the
next three years, Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment secretary, announced
yesterday.
This is part of the government's strategy of focusing resources on practical
help for job-seekers, she told MPs.
During a Labour-originated debate on unemployment, Mrs Shephard also said an
extra 180,000 new places were to be provided next year in Jobclubs and on
the Job Interview Guarantee Scheme. Job Review Workshops will get an
additional 10,000 places.
The figures confirm, as indicated last month at the time of the Autumn
Statement, that the government intends to target a greater proportion of
funds on non-training initiatives. Expenditure on training programmes is to
suffer a 3 per cent cut in real terms.
Mrs Shephard said the career development loans - which are provided by the
clearing banks with the government paying interest until training has been
completed - would be available for people in and out of work.
The government's focus in drawing up its plans was on individuals in
greatest need and measures that had proved themselves successful, she said.
Mr Frank Dobson, the shadow employment secretary, placed his emphasis on
training, claiming that the government's training budget per unemployed
person was less than half of what it had been only 'three short years ago'.
Statistics showed the unemployed stood less of a chance of getting a job if
they had been on employment training than if they had not, Mr Dobson argued.
The Autumn Statement had been 'so feeble' that Ms Shephard and her
colleagues had refused to estimate how many jobs it might create.
Labour's motion attacking the government's 'total failure' to tackle rising
unemployment was defeated by 309 votes to 276, a government majority of 33.
</TEXT>
