<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM attacked over EC role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OPPOSITION leaders rounded on Mr John Major's presidency of the European
Community yesterday with Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, claiming he had
'incompetently and humiliatingly bungled' an opportunity to shape the EC's
future.
The attack was joined by Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, who
charged the prime minister with reducing British influence in the EC by
lacking authority and by failing to give a clear lead.
With Whitehall officials apparently systematically trying to lower hopes of
substantial breakthroughs at the Edinburgh summit at the weekend, both
opposition party leaders were yesterday preparing to pin all the blame on Mr
Major.
At Commons' questions, the prime minister seemed to be taking the same
approach as officials, leading to speculation that his strategy is to lower
hopes deliberately in order to make any agreements eventually reached appear
important victories.
Questioned from his own benches, Mr Major warned that 'a large number of
very complex' issues remained outstanding, ranging from the EC budget,
enlargement of the Community and the so-called Danish problem.
The prime minister said Britain had the lowest corporation tax among the G7
countries and the lowest interest rates in the EC.
He also insisted, to cheers from Conservatives, that there was no question
of Britain allowing its budget rebate to be cut if the question was raised
by other member states at the summit.
Mrs Jacqui Lait (C Hastings and Rye) offered Mr Major the 'total support' of
Tory backbenchers in resisting pressure to give ground on the rebate.
Pressed by Mr Smith to explain why jobs were not at the top of the agenda,
Mr Major said Treasury officials had been touring the Continent to seek
agreement on a Community-wide growth strategy.
'I very much hope that co-ordinated measures will emerge from those
discussion, but we will have to wait and see what our European partners also
feel at Edinburgh,' he said.
In reply, Mr Smith underlined that proposals to stimulate the EC economy
with research and development funding through infrastructure programmes and
job-creation measures had all come from other member states.
Downing Street officials made clear later, however, that the shape of the
package set to be tabled at the summit centres squarely on proposals made
public some time ago.
These comprise policies endorsed in the Autumn Statement on public spending,
stressing capital spending programmes and restraints on public sector wage
costs.
A Tory Euro MP said yesterday that Britain was proposing a deal at the
summit to waste more than Pounds 500m of taxpayers' money over the next five
years by perpetuating the EC government's 'travelling circus'.
Mr Peter Price, MEP for London South East, said the heads of government
would be invited by the British presidency to endorse a plan to retain the
existing arrangement - a debating chamber in Strasbourg, staff offices for
3,000 in Luxembourg and committee rooms and offices for MEPs in Brussels.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
