<TEXT>
A TOTAL OF 60,000 career development loans are to be made available over the
next three years, Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment secretary, announced
yesterday.
This is part of the government's strategy of focusing resources on practical
help for job-seekers, she told MPs.
During a Labour-originated debate on unemployment, Mrs Shephard also said an
extra 180,000 new places were to be provided next year in Jobclubs and on
the Job Interview Guarantee Scheme. Job Review Workshops will get an
additional 10,000 places.
The figures confirm, as indicated last month at the time of the Autumn
Statement, that the government intends to target a greater proportion of
overall funds on such non-training initiatives. Expenditure on training
programmes is to suffer a cut in real terms of 3 per cent.
Running the gauntlet of a string of Labour MPs making interventions on
specific plant closures, Mrs Shephard said the career development loans  -
which are provided by the clearing banks with the government paying interest
until training has been completed - would be available for people in and out
