<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / Funds pledged for London health services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUBSTANTIAL funds have been set aside next year to improve health services
in London, Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, said yesterday while
announcing financial allocations to regional health authorities.
The extra money will help introduce the proposals of Sir Bernard Tomlinson's
report into the capital's healthcare. This recommended reducing hospital
beds and developing family doctor and community services.
However, the amount the government intends to commit in 1993-94 will not be
known until the new year, when Mrs Bottomley decides on the Tomlinson
report's recommendations.
Under the overall financial allocations for 1993-94 announced yesterday, the
four Thames regions covering London and the south-east will receive
increases of 0.4 per cent over forecast inflation.
Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, said: 'I understand the
government intend to fund their programme of hospital closures in London by
means of loans from the other regions. This is a cruel trick that Mrs
Bottomley has yet to formally announce.' He added that the government's
figures failed to take into account numerous factors including the rapidly
ageing population.
The government is moving towards allocating health funds based on the size
and demographic characteristics of regional populations. If this formula
applied fully next year, three of the four Thames regions - south-west,
north-east and north-west - would suffer budget cuts of between Pounds 13m
and Pounds 26m.
This reflects the declining population of inner London, a long-term trend
significant in this year's allocation because 1991 census data was used for
the first time.
The biggest funding increases next year will go to the population-growth
regions of Wessex, East Anglia, South-West and Trent. Mrs Bottomley has
allocated a total Pounds 17.5bn to the regions, retaining Pounds 2.66bn for
purposes such as the London restructuring and Aids services.
She also announced that a further 121 hospitals and other services had
expressed interest in becoming self-governing trusts from April 1994. If
most are approved, the drive to local self-management that started with last
year's health reforms will be almost complete.
Management, Page 11
</TEXT>
