<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / Shadow of Indian unrest falls on Britain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A fireman surveys the aftermath of a blaze that swept through the West
Bromwich Shree Krishna Hindu Temple in the early hours of yesterday morning
during a spate of attacks on Hindu centres in Birmingham, Bolton, Bradford,
Coventry and Derby, Paul Cheeseright writes.
An emergency meeting of Moslem leaders is being held in London today by the
International Moslems Organisation. It is expected to appeal for calm after
the attacks, which follow the destruction in India of an ancient Moslem
mosque at Ayodhya. The organisation said: 'We don't want the violence to
spread.' Yesterday in the areas where the attacks took place meetings were
held by police and community groups that led to statements of inter-communal
support.
Police appeals for information about men seen close to the temples in West
Bromwich and Coventry before and after the attacks indicated that little is
known about the identity of the culprits. Police said two white men were
seen near the Hindu temple in Harnell Lane, Coventry, around the time it was
attacked, making premature any judgment that this incident was the result of
tension between ethnic minorities.
In the borough of Sandwell, of which West Bromwich is a part, the Indian,
Pakistani and Bangladeshi communities make up more than 10 per cent of the
population of 290,100. There are more than 9,600 Hindus and more than 7,700
Moslems. Damage to the Shree Krishna temple, which was attacked at about
3am, is estimated at millions of pounds. The fire was brought under control
by 70 firemen before the interior of the temple was completely destroyed.
A Hindu temple in Derby was severely damaged but attacks at the Vishwa
temple in Bolton, the Hindu Cultural Centre in Bradford and temples in
Sparkbrook, Birmingham, and in Coventry caused minimal damage.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-3239</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLJACABTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921209
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / BR freight customers unite to protest at price rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LOBBY GROUP representing British Rail's freight customers yesterday warned
that price increases imposed by BR were in danger of driving 2m tonnes of
freight a year - equivalent to 80,000 truckloads - on to the roads.
The newly formed Freight on Rail group said BR's price rises conflicted with
environmental goals and the government's policy of encouraging road freight
to switch to rail.
Freight on Rail, claiming the support of more than 150 companies including
BR freight customers, rail wagon manufacturers and other railway equipment
suppliers, said BR was seeking to increase freight rates by 80 per cent to
120 per cent.
Customers had decided to switch 700,000 tonnes of bulk freight such as
cement and oil to road, the group said, adding that a total of 2m tonnes of
freight a year was in jeopardy. About 90 per cent of conventional container
traffic could also switch to road, it claimed.
Mr Mike Harvey, general manager of CAIB UK, a wagon-leasing group, said the
price rises appeared aimed at reducing BR's freight operations to a
profitable core in readiness for privatisation.
He and other Freight on Rail members feared that lower freight flows would
mean higher costs because overheads would have to be shared.
'We are getting to the stage where you no longer have a critical mass, and
when that critical mass is not there you no longer have a railfreight
industry,' Mr Harvey said.
BR's Trainload Freight subsidiary said it had increased prices only for
traffic which otherwise had no viable future on the railway. 'We are under a
government remit which requires us to operate commercially,' it said. 'We
cannot keep traffic which does not make a positive financial return.'
Continental train operators using Britain's railway tracks after January 1
will pay the same rates as those already agreed for Channel tunnel traffic,
the Department of Transport announced yesterday.
However, the deal will be short-lived because it will be superseded by a
radically different track charging regime due to take effect with rail
privatisation in April 1994.
It will affect little traffic before then because the Channel tunnel is not
due to open until December next year. The only access to Britain for
Continental trains will be by the daily SNCF (French railways) train ferry
from Dover to Dunkirk.
The charges were published yesterday in response to an EC directive
requiring member nations to open their tracks to international passenger and
freight trains from January 1.
</TEXT>
