<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / Industry gas costs rise by 4.2%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FUEL costs for large industrial gas users have risen 4.2 per cent in the
past year, in spite of British Gas cutting prices to domestic customers.
The increase was the second highest recorded in a survey of international
gas prices by National Utility Services (NUS), the consultancy.
British Gas has raised the price for companies receiving an interruptible
service, meaning they can be cut off at short notice - a service for which
they have traditionally paid very low prices.
Mr Andrew Johns, director of NUS, said: 'Any UK manufacturing company on an
interruptible contract would not be at a competitive advantage compared with
its competitors in the countries we surveyed. In fact it would be at a major
disadvantage.'
The UK ranks sixth out of nine countries when comparing the price charged to
business users. But NUS stressed it is inthe bulk-volume, low-pricesector of
the industrial market - which has not been penetrated by rivals to British
Gas - that prices are rising most rapidly.
By comparison German industrial users have seen their gas costs fall by 22
per cent over the past year. The UK was beaten by Belgium, which raised gas
prices by 5 per cent last year.
Sweden is the most expensive country in gas costs to big users.
Mr Ian Powe, chairman of the Gas Consumers Council, who warned on Monday
that big users would face substantial price rises, said the survey 'tends to
confirm the view that some sectors of the industrial market are seeing no
benefit from competition'.
Mr Cedric Brown, chief executive of British Gas, yesterday said in a speech
marking the sixth anniversary of the company's privatisation that domestic
prices for gas had fallen by more than 20 per cent in real terms since 1986.
At the same time, contract prices (to non-interruptible industrial users)
dropped 25 per cent in real terms.
Mr Peter Rost, chairman of the Major Energy Users' Council, said there was
increasing concern among his members that interruptible gas will become less
available and rise in price.
</TEXT>
