FT  09 DEC 92 / Fimbra row over new watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL ADVISERS yest-erday expressed disquiet about the proposed
formation of the Personal Investment Authority, which would take over the
role of Fimbra, their self-regulatory body.
Many members dissented from the governing council's support for the new
body, intended to merge Fimbra with Lautro, the self-regulatory body for the
life insurance and unit trust industries along with some members of Imro,
the fund managers' body.
The PIA has been proposed because of Fimbra's inability to raise enough
money from members to regulate its area effectively and to make its full
share of contributions to the Investors' Compensation Scheme. Life companies
have capped Fimbra's compensation scheme liabilities in the past two years.
Mr Paul Beard of the Cheshire-based Alexander Beard Group said the
independent status of advisers should be clearly disclosed, adding that the
levy to meet advisers' obligations under the investors' compensation scheme
would put many Fimbra members out of business if the PIA was not accepted.
Mr David Kauders, a Taunton-based fee-charging financial adviser, called on
the council to relate compensation-scheme contributions to capacity to pay
instead of establishing the PIA.
Mr Michael Bryant, marketing director of Rathbone Brothers, referred to the
'implicit blackmail threat' of the life companies not to cap Fimbra
liabilities for this year unless Fimbra votes for the PIA.
Mr Bryant questioned what he said was a change in Fimbra's accounting policy
last year to treat deferred subscriptions and registration fees in its
balance sheet as capital and reserves rather than creditors.
Sir Gordon Downey, chairman of Fimbra, said this was the most accurate place
for them as they were monies already received and not returnable.
Sir Gordon said the PIA would bring together all those concerned with the
personal investor under one umbrella, enabling 'a level playing field to be
established'.
It provided the opportunity for consistent standards of regulation, which
would help eliminate the confusion caused by a multiplicity of regulators,
said Sir Gordon, who is also chairman of the PIA shadow board.
Banks and building societies have refused to join the PIA, arguing they are
regulated directly by the Securities and Investments Board, while many say
they do not wish to stand behind the potential liabilities of all financial
advisers.
</TEXT>
