FT  09 DEC 92 / Fears on jobless training scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONCERN that recently unemployed people who want training in skill shortage
areas are to be denied access to the government's new training and work
experience scheme has been expressed in a report by Full Employment UK, the
consultancy and training company.
The Training for Work scheme, announced last month by Mrs Gillian Shephard,
employment secretary, will combine Employment Training and Employment
Action, the work experience scheme.
The report, drawn up after consultation with Training and Enterprise
Councils, which administer government-funded training programmes in England
and Wales, broadly welcomed the new scheme. It said the eligibility rules
were relatively wide, but it criticised the exclusion of people who had been
unemployed for less than six months - currently 18 per cent of entrants to
ET.
The report also said that the new Jobplan workshops, which will be run by
the department's Employment Service and which people unemployed for 12
months will have to attend, could be used to dump people on the new scheme.
The level of awareness in the leisure industry of the new national
vocational qualifications is generally poor, a survey of over 70 companies
employing 260,000 people says.
In the survey, conducted by consultant Mrs Janet Salmon between July and
November, 35 per cent of respondents were implementing pilot NVQ programmes
and 24 per cent had plans to introduce them.
But 41 per cent said they did not intend to implement them. Reasons included
the 'prohibitive costs' of certification and claims that existing training
was at a higher, more comprehensive standard.
