<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / WEU urged to intervene in Bosnia conflict
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WESTERN European countries should take more effective military measures to
deal with the Bosnian crisis, Mr Wim Van Eekelen, secretary-general of the
Western European Union, said yesterday.
The measures should include establishment of 'safe havens' for the Moslem
population of Bosnia, as western allies had done for Kurds in northern Iraq,
and the provision of military air cover for aid convoys.
At a final press conference in London before the 10-nation defence
organisation moves its headquarters to Brussels next month, Mr Van Eekelen
said the UN operation in Bosnia had probably reached its limits, as far as
peace-keeping was concerned.
He did not think either China or Russia would agree to UN military
involvement in Bosnia beyond its present task of providing protection for
humanitarian aid convoys. That was why he believed the European countries
should take a lead, if necessary outside the UN context.
Mr van Eekelen recognised the reluctance of all countries to become heavily
engaged with ground forces in the former Yugoslavia. But the European
countries should set themselves more limited objectives and then make sure
that they were attained, which was not the case at present. 'Military
measures are sometimes necessary to achieve political objectives,' he said.
'Our credibility is zero politically because we are just not doing
anything.'
Mr van Eekelen said that while the joint Nato-WEU naval blockade in the
Adriatic had been successful in preventing supplies reaching Serbia and
Montenegro by sea, much tighter controls had to be imposed to prevent
sanctions-busting on the Danube.
Aircraft should be provided to protect aid convoys and should be authorised
to fire back if a convoy was attacked or remove obstacles in its way.
Mr van Eekelen said a more dynamic and independent European defence posture
was necessary with the withdrawal of US troops from Europe.
Though he hoped some American forces would stay, the only chance of
preserving Nato as a viable organisation was to transform it into a genuine
two-pillar alliance. It was no longer just a question of burden-sharing, but
of a more equal partnership.
</TEXT>
