FT  09 DEC 92 / Concern at Europol HQ row
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE establishment of a permanent headquarters for Europol, the planned
European criminal intelligence agency, is facing potentially a long-term
delay because of differences between EC member states, police officials said
yesterday, write Jimmy Burns in London and Andrew Hill in Brussels.
Detective Superintendent Ian Morrison, the UK delegate at Europol's pilot
offices in Strasbourg, said that in the unlikely event that agreement is
reached at the Edinburgh summit, it could take at least six months before
Europol can become functional.
'There appears to be general agreement on the terms of reference of Europol
but the issue of location is undecided and without it Europol cannot start,'
Mr Morrison said.
Sharp differences over the location of Europol, which was due to start a
drugs unit on January 1 surfaced last week during a meeting of EC interior
ministers in London.
Political passions are such that Dutch officials publicly alleged last week
that France was attempting to discredit The Hague's candidacy for the
institution by accusing the Dutch government of failing to curb the sale of
soft drugs. It is thought likely that the dispute may only be resolved when
there is a wider trade-off over other future permanent locations of key EC
institutions.
