<HEADLINE>
FT  09 DEC 92 / Ford to raise prices by up to 10% in January
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD yesterday announced plans to increase car prices by between 4 1/2 per
cent and 10 per cent, surprising the industry and provoking consumer group
and political protests.
Ford, which has made heavy losses and whose UK market leadership is under
severe pressure, blamed the rises on sterling's devaluation and other cost
increases.
The rises - effective from January 3 - include 7.5 per cent increases for
Sierras and Granadas and are larger than any imposed or indicated by rivals.
The Consumers' Association and opposition politicians said Ford appeared to
be seeking to lead the industry, not consumers, in reaping the benefits of
the recent abolition of 5 per cent special car tax, averaging Pounds 400 a
car.
Ford rejected the allegation, saying: 'Our costs have risen far more than
the increases we have put forward as a result of the devaluation.'
Nevertheless, its move was seen as a potentially risky gamble by some
industry analysts. As market leader for many years, Ford has led several
rounds of increases and been able to rely on rivals following suit.
But Vauxhall is challenging its leadership. With other rivals professing
little inclination towards further rises, Ford may find itself isolated
while bearing the brunt of consumer criticism over the already stormy issue
of perceived high UK car prices.
Rover said it had no plans to raise prices, as did Vauxhall, which announced
a 3.25 per cent rise just before car tax was abolished. German
manufacturers, worst hit by devaluation, have already put up prices and may
raise them again in the new year.
Mr Stephen Locke, the Consumers' Association's director of policy, said
Ford's move 'confirms all our worst fears about the manufacturers' desire to
see the UK as a high-price, high-profit market'.
Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour spokesman on consumer affairs, accused the
industry of failing to pass on car tax savings. 'The chancellor is being
walked over by the manufacturers,' he said.
Mr Garel Rhys, professor of motor industry economics at Cardiff Business
School, said the rises may indicate a strategy change by Ford to a lower
market share but with profitable sales.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
