<DOCNO>FT924-3308</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLOCCAGZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921208
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 92 / Bucking The Trend: Precision approach to following the
market - An engineering group's recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STAINLESS Metalcraft seems to have experienced the economic cycle the wrong
way round. In the second half of the 1980s, when many were enjoying what
some regarded as an economic miracle, company profits were plummeting. Now,
in the depths of recession, profits are rising sharply.
As if to commemorate the reverse, the company is changing its name of
Ferraris. That may not strike a chord among the few who trade its shares on
the unlisted securities market, but the cognoscenti of the medical equipment
market will recognise it. So will those who use its asthma monitoring
equipment.
More than that, the new name is testimony that the company has manoeuvred
itself into the medical equipment sector, dropping, for example, general
engineering.
Mr Kenneth Baker, the chairman, said: 'You attack a market which is there,
rather than one which is disappearing.' Mr Baker cut his professional teeth
at Metal Box and subsequently worked in US, German and other British groups.
In the financial year to last August, Stainless Metalcraft, having made
losses in three of the four preceding years, had pre-tax profits of Pounds
353,000. There should be more this year, and the company has Singer &amp;
Friedlander, the merchant bank, helping it in a search for acquisitions.
Mr Baker said the losses were the result of 'a self-inflicted wound'.
Stainless Metalcraft was a sub-contractor to a sub-contractor on a storage
system for British Nuclear Fuels' waste. It was an unusually big contract
for the company: the work was delivered on time, but obtaining payment
turned into a welter of argument and arbitration. By the time the matter was
settled, the management had become hardened to adversity and the recession
had started. Stainless Metalcraft felt it early, 'when people started to
reduce capital spending, which was our area of business', as Mr Baker put
it.
The company's strategy was, in short, 'to get out of metal bashing' and to
develop the company along the lines of precision engineering 'with wider
shareholdings and wider interests', Mr Baker said.
The wider shareholdings meant diluting the interest of the Childs family,
which now stands at 25 per cent. The development meant driving the company
into higher-value-added, higher-technology products in the medical equipment
area. Ferraris Instruments had been bought in 1986. Production settled at
sites in Chatteris, Cambridgeshire - which generates about 70 per cent of
turnover - Kettering, in Northamptonshire; north London; and Ohio in the US.
'All through the recession, the company has continued to invest in
production equipment and the development of new products,' said Mr Baker.
There has been concentration on 'improving productivity by improving methods
of manufacturing in conjunction with our major customers.' The biggest
customer is Oxford Magnet Technology, part of Oxford Instruments, for which
Stainless Metalcraft has been making components for scanners and
co-operating on design and manufacturing techniques.
The result has been that the value of output for each Stainless Metalcraft
employee has risen over the past three years from Pounds 35,000 to Pounds
58,000 a year. There is another side: as is usually the case with
manufacturing investment, the more that is invested, the less the
employment. At Chatteris 150 people are employed; in 1988 there were 350.
Further, the company is on a financial tightrope. There are no complaints in
the boardroom about banks. 'We needed a lot of support to enable us to stand
our corner,' Mr Baker said. They still do.
Support came from Barclays, with generous overdraft and loan facilities, as
the percentage of debt relative to net assets went up from 70 in 1989, to 95
in 1990, and then to 154 last year, before coming down to 98 this year.
Ferraris, then, has to keep a steady balance to stay on the tightrope.
Still, there is some stability in the medical equipment market. Demand has
kept up, in spite of the recession, but, Mr Baker said, 'there is pressure
to keep down prices. If you can maintain your competitiveness, you can
maintain your market share.'
</TEXT>
