<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 92 / DTI will delay research grants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW RESEARCH grants or contracts from the Department of Trade and Industry
may be unavailable until April 1994 because the Pounds 110m-a-year DTI
innovation budget is overspent, the department has told researchers
unofficially.
Mr John Bennett, secretary general of the Association of Independent
Research and Technology Organisations, said some of his 36 member companies
had 'expressed very serious concern' about the moratorium.
Several organisations expected to receive new DTI funds next year to replace
expiring contracts. If funds do not arrive, they will have to shed
scientists and engineers.
About 10 research and technology organisations will suffer badly, said Mr
Ian Cooper, chairman of the association's policy committee and chief
executive of BHR Group, an engineering research body. The loss to his own
company would be about Pounds 1m next year. There would be the direct loss
of Pounds 700,000 in DTI funds, and that might lead to industry withdrawing
a further Pounds 300,000. 'That's a big chunk of our Pounds 7m turnover and
it will inevitably mean getting rid of some research teams,' he said.
Mr Douglas Munro, managing director of the British Textile Technology Group,
said: 'This is very bad news for R&amp;D work across the board. And it means
that some specific bright ideas from which industry would benefit are never
going to happen.'
One casualty of the DTI freeze on new R&amp;D spending is a Pounds 1.5m
environmental project involving five research organisations to develop
systems for removing pollutants from industrial effluents with immobilised
enzymes.
Mr Brian McCarthy, BTTG biotechnology manager, said: 'It is a field in which
the UK could quickly dominate world markets and the initial reaction from
DTI was very favourable; they said it was just the sort of work that should
be supported. So there is general dismay that it is not going to survive the
moratorium.'
Officially the DTI says there is no moratorium on new research programmes.
Until Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, has decided
the department's 1993-94 innovation budget, 'officials are taking a cautious
line', the department said.
The heads of several research organisations insist that they have been told
privately by DTI officials that 'there will be no money for anything new
until the end of 1993-94', as one executive said.
</TEXT>
