FT  08 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Labour MP seeks probe into Clarke Foods
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LABOUR MP last night urged the government to launch an investigation into
the collapse of Clarke Foods, Britain's second largest ice-cream
manufacturer, which went into administrative receivership last October
leaving debts of about Pounds 25m.
Mr George Howarth, MP for Knowsley North and former Labour frontbench
housing spokesman, also questioned share sales by chairman Mr Henry D Clarke
and fellow director Mr Martin Riley.
The two directors sold shares from their pension funds weeks before the
share price began a steady fall to the suspension price of 8p.
Mr Neil Hamilton, Corporate affairs Minister, agreed to request an interim
report from the receivers, Robson Rhodes, while describing Mr Howarth's
request for an official investigation under the Companies Act as premature.
Mr Howarth, whose constituency includes the Clarke factory in Merseyside
which was briefly occupied by angry workers following the receivership, was
speaking in a Commons debate on redundancies at the company.
He also said that Nestle, the foods group which bought much of the business
and assets of Clarke, had decided to close the Merseyside factory.
He alleged that Mr Clarke and Mr Riley 'clearly must have known that Clarke
Foods was in severe difficulties' at the time they sold the shares. 'Were Mr
Clarke and Mr Riley guilty of insider dealing?' he asked.
The Labour MP called for the interim report to include 'any preliminary
evidence of fraud and/or insider dealing'.
Mr Howarth also asked for an investigation into the state of Pounds 1.4m
allocated for severance and pension payments to employees at one of Clarke's
factories.
Mr Howarth finally called on the government to launch an inquiry in to the
fitness of Mr Clarke to be a director of a UK quoted company.
