<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 92 / Inmos venture with HK company will save jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INMOS, the UK-based semi-conductor company, is forming a new company with
QPL International Holdings, a Hong Kong-based electronic components maker,
which will enable it to keep open its south Wales factory and save 220 jobs.
The new company, Newport Wafer Fab, will be 70 per cent owned by QPL and 30
per cent by Inmos, which is a wholly owned subsidiary of SGS-Thomson, the
Franco-Italian semiconductor group. The Welsh Office is providing regional
selective assistance.
In addition, QPL expects to create 280 jobs over the next three years by
upgrading the facility, and more than treble annual output at Newport by
1996.
QPL will offer semiconductor foundry services to companies that design
semiconductors but do not own a manufacturing facility. The company has
foundries in the US and in Japan.
The deal shows the growth of Far Eastern companies in electronics. QPL, a
subcontractor of Inmos and SGS-Thomson, has raised turnover by 44 per cent
to more than HKDollars 1bn (Pounds 85.6m), with profits in excess of
HKDollars 171m.
</TEXT>
