<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 92 / Walker insists funds for coal review are sufficient
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD WALKER, the former Conservative cabinet minister selected to oversee
the regeneration of coalfield areas, insisted yesterday that the Pounds 165m
allocated by the government was sufficient for the task in the coming 12
months.
On his first public visit to a coalfield since his appointment in October,
Lord Walker said he wanted more government money to continue the
regeneration effort - using his first-year experience to assess how much was
needed.
'As far as future years are concerned, when I've got down to the detail of
the task I would discuss with the government departments what was required,'
he said.
Suggestions that the funding was inadequate were a myth, he said. 'I have a
reputation of not being backward in asking for money I need.'
Citing his track record as Welsh secretary, Lord Walker said successful
regeneration programmes did not increase public expenditure, since they
reduced unemployment and social security payments and brought in taxpaying
activities.
The appointment of Lord Walker, energy secretary during the 1984-85 miners'
strike, to lead coalfield regeneration was announced by Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, after the public outcry over the
proposed closure of 31 pits.
Yesterday's visit to the Durham coalfield was at the invitation of the local
authorities' East Durham task force. A year ago the task force said the area
needed Pounds 158m investment to have any chance of recovery from 10,000
mining jobs losses since 1981. It now faces the closure of its last two
pits, employing more than 2,000 men.
Lord Walker disclosed that he recently privately visited the Nottinghamshire
and west Midlands coalfields. He emphasised that his visits did not pre-empt
the outcome of the government's pit closures review.
</TEXT>
