FT  08 DEC 92 / Lionhope Pounds 500m development to be scaled down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BACKERS of a controversial Pounds 500m package of commercial and residential
developments in one of the south-east's unemployment blackspots are
proposing a scaled-down version to address environmental objections.
Touche Ross, the accountancy firm, and Citibank, the US bank, are discussing
with the government, local authorities and environmental groups a new
version of the Lionhope plan on and around the Isle of Sheppey in north-east
Kent.
The 'son of Lionhope' proposal is the latest twist in a saga that began with
the administrative receivership in 1989 of the developer Lionhope (Kent),
which devised the original project. The plans were rejected in July by Mr
Michael Howard, the environment secretary, after a 13-week public inquiry in
1990 during which environmentalists condemned the effect on local wildlife.
In September, Touche Ross - Lionhope's receiver - said it would challenge
the decision in the High Court.
The projects' promoters have been discussing revised proposals with Kent
County Council, Swale Borough Council and the main objectors, English Nature
and the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds.
Mr Tony Houghton, joint administrative receiver, said yesterday he was
'quite confident that we have put forward a proposal that fully meets
objections raised at the public inquiry.' The revised plan, based on four
sites, still hopes to create 9,000 jobs, and one of its key elements, a big
expansion of Sheerness Dock, remains unchanged.
A proposed privately funded tunnel under the Swale, linking Sheppey to the
mainland, will be replaced with a bridge, to be funded mainly by the
government.
</TEXT>
