</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SLOVENIA has bucked the trend of Balkan nationalism as moderates yesterday
emerged as the biggest winners in the first elections since the republic won
independence from Yugoslavia last year, writes Laura Silber in Ljubljana.
Mr Milan Kucan, the incumbent, won re-election as president with 64 per cent
of Sunday's ballot, according to official results with more than half the
vote counted.
The centrist Liberal Democrats (LDS) led the vote for a 130-seat bicameral
parliament, with 23 per cent. The Christian Democrats received 14.9 per cent
and the United Left 13.26 per cent. Mr Janez Drnovsek, prime minister and
head of the LDS, said talks would soon begin on forming a coalition.
