<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 92 / Accord reached on airline landing slots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Community transport ministers agreed early today on a system
designed to help smaller airlines get better access to landing slots at
major EC airports, EC officials said, Reuter reports from Brussels.
The system tightens rules under which airlines lose slots they don't use,
but falls short of a proposal to confiscate slots from major airlines to
make room for smaller ones.
As a result, it is likely to be criticised by smaller airlines such as
British Midland and Virgin Atlantic which have campaigned for firm EC action
to help them compete on the EC market and offer lower fares in time for the
EC's January 1 single market deadline.
Under the accord, which must be formalised at a future meeting of EC
ministers, airlines holding fewer than four slots at a particular airport
will qualify for slots which become available under the system.
The rules would be especially needed at the heavily congested airports of
Paris Orly, London Heathrow and Frankfurt.
EC transport ministers yesterday agreed to explore emergency steps to rescue
EC airline companies from their current crisis and set minimum fare prices,
according to French Transport Minister Jean-Louis Bianco.
He said that between 1990 and 1993 the air transport sector was expected to
lose about Dollars 10bn and that the crisis, harmful in the short term for
airlines, could soon be detrimental to passengers too.
Citing steps that could be taken, the French minister said the EC could
invoke a safeguard clause enabling it to put a floor under fare prices and
protect EC airlines from 'ruinous competition'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
