<HEADLINE>
FT  08 DEC 92 / Indian forces rout militants at mosque
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SHIRAZ SIDHVA and STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW DELHI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDIAN police early today stormed a disputed site in Ayodhya where thousands
of Hindu militants destroyed an ancient mosque on Sunday.
Four battalions, numbering 5,000 police, and a rapid action commando force
used tear gas and rubber bullets but there were no casualties. They met
little resistance although militants stoned them as they approached.
Delhi decided on a resolute show of force after the destruction of the
mosque, in northern India, provoked communal violence throughout the country
in which at least 220 people were killed. Mr PV Narasimha Rao, the prime
minister, was due to make a statement in parliament this morning. He
yesterday faced intense criticism for his failure to protect the mosque at a
weekend rally called by the right-wing Hindu Bharatiya Janata party (BJP),
the main opposition party.
At dawn today the government arrested the leader of the BJP, Mr LK Advani,
who yesterday took responsibility for the assault and resigned as
parliamentary opposition leader.
The officer in charge of the Ayodhya operation, Mr PN Ramakrishnan, said:
'The boys have been very fast and very smart. We simply scared them.' The
police then secured control of the town itself and despatched the militants
on buses and trucks to the nearby city of Lucknow.
There had been fears of a bloody confrontation with the estimated 50,000
extremists who had seized the sacred Hindu site, where a mosque was built in
the 16th century.
The government was urged yesterday to ban militant religious organisations,
including the Rashtriya Swayam Sevak Sangh and the Vishwa Hindu Parishad,
the extremist groups which support the BJP.
Despite demands from MPs from other opposition parties for Mr Rao's
resignation, it seemed that the ruling Congress (I) party would rally around
the prime minister for the sake of stability. Congress blamed the BJP for
the assault and condemned it as 'the greatest political tragedy which has
overtaken the nation since the assassination of Mahatma Gandhi'.
Protests from abroad included condemnation from Pakistan, where the
government called a nationwide strike for today.
Moslem MPs urged the government to rebuild the mosque as a shrine to
national reconciliation. They were supported by many Congress MPs. However,
it was difficult to see how it could be rebuilt in the face of intense Hindu
opposition.
Across India, the army was deployed and curfews imposed in several areas as
communal riots swept through almost every state, and the toll of victims -
mainly Moslems - mounted rapidly. In Bombay more than 40 people died in
clashes involving 10,000 protesters.
There was also violence in Ahmedabad, New Delhi and the walled city of
Jaipur. Calcutta was paralysed by a strike called by trade unionists.
Tensions spilled over during the day to India's predominantly Moslem
neighbours, Pakistan and Bangladesh.
Ayodhya's woes, Page 4
A country split along its deepest fault line, Page 15
</TEXT>
